<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First ASEAN Business Summit Ends in Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The first ASEAN business summit
ended here this evening with calls for political stability and
reduced red tape in the interest of economic development in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the end of the meeting, which was described as
successful, Chairman of the ASEAN Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Aburizal Bakrie said that participants were optimistic about
ASEAN's future economic development and believe that economic
development needs political stability in their respective
countries.
</P>
<P>
They urged the governments and the business community to make
common efforts to reduce the gap between rich and poor, especially
the gaps between cities and villages.
</P>
<P>
In an era of free trade and global market, the representatives
said, the governments should raise their working efficiency by
reducing bureaucracy and introducing more deregulation policies.
</P>
<P>
They said the human resources development and education should
be intensified to maintain ASEAN's remarkable economic growth it
has achieved over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
The summit also called on the governments in ASEAN countries to
promote private participation in their economic construction.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit, organized by the ASEAN Chamber of Commerce
and Industry, was attended by some 600 businessmen, including
those from non-ASEAN countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, ASEAN senior officials delivered speeches
on different subjects on the grouping's future development,
especially the challenges in the face of globalization.
</P>
<P>
There were five major topics during the meeting -- food
business and agriculture, automotive industry, finance, franchise
and infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations) groups Brunei,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The next ASEAN business summit will be held in Kuala Lumpur,
Malaysia, in 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
