<HEADLINE> UN Chief to Visit S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan will visit South Africa next week at
the invitation of President Nelson Mandela, a source said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela extended his invitation to Annan when he met the U.N.
Chief during the World Economic Forum meeting in Davos,
Switzerland earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to hold talks with Annan in Cape Town
about African mediation efforts in seeking a lasting solution to
the conflict in Zaire, said the source.
</P>
<P>
However, Presidential aide Parks Mankahlana said in Cape Town
that Annan's scheduled visit to the country was "very broad" and
would not center solely on African and United Nations mediation
efforts in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
During his state visit to Singapore last week, Mandela called
for the world body to be restructured to reflect the changing
nature of society and to prevent smaller nations from being
swallowed up by the economically powerful.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the dominance of post World War II powers on the
U.N. Security Council, Mandela said the world body was still
structured on the basis of outdated security concerns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
