<HEADLINE> S. Africa Denies Striking Deal on Lome Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Department
of Trade and Industry today dismissed spreading rumors of the
finalization of an agreement with the European Union (EU)
granting the country access to the Lome Convention.
</P>
<P>
"No deal has officially been secured between the European
Union and South Africa on qualified access in terms of the Lome
Convention to the EU by the republic," the Department said in a
statement here.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations were continuing and the discussions would revolve
around the EU and South African regulatory trade environment, but
would not deal specifically with the trade and development, said
the statement.
</P>
<P>
South African and EU officials have been negotiating in
Brussels on the former's access to the Lome Convention, a trade
and aid treaty between the EU and 70 African, Caribbean and
Pacific states that ensures preferential access to the European
market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
