<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Buy More Gas from Myanmar Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The PTT Exploration and Production
(PTTEP) of Thailand today signed another contract with Myanmar's
state oil company to purchase natural gas from the country's
Yedagun Field in addition to the Yadana Field in the gulf of
Mottama.
</P>
<P>
Official Radio Myanmar said tonight that the contract was
reached among the PTTEP, a subsidiary of the Petroleum Authority
of Thailand, Myanmar Oil and Gas Enterprise (MOGE), Texaco of the
United States, Premier of Britain and Nippon of Japan, which have
been jointly developing the field on a production sharing basis
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Yedagun Field has gas reserves of 1.2 trillion cubic-feet
and crude oil of 2 billion barrels, and the gas will be sold to
Thailand beginning 1999 at a rate of 200 million cubic-feet per
day, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Under the first 30-year contract, which the PTTEP signed with
the MOGE in January 1995, natural gas from Myanmar's Yadana Field
being developed by TOTAL of France and UNOCAL of the United States
since 1992 in the gulf of Mottama will be sold to the PTTEP at a
rate of 525 million cubic-feet per day starting July 1998.
</P>
<P>
A 430-km long pipeline is being laid across Myanmar-Thai border
areas for transportation of gas to Thailand. The Yadana Field has
an estimated gas reserves of 6.7 trillion cubic-feet.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Myanmar has signed over 20
production-sharing contracts with oil companies from nearly 10
countries including Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia, Thailand and the United States, exploring oil and gas in
different offshore and onshore areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in the oil and gas sector had reached 1.5
billion U.S. dollars in 32 permitted projects by the end of
January 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
