<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Ready to Take Up Responsibility for Zaire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- France said today that it is ready
to take up its responsibility in an international operation for
saving tens of thousands of refugees stranded in eastern Zaire
where fighting is going on between Zairean government forces and
Tutsi rebels.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Jacques Rummelhardt said that
faced with "the catastrophic situation of refugees and displaced
people," France is ready to "assume its responsibility" within "an
international device of humanitarian security provision."
</P>
<P>
"In the case that -- contrary to what we have not ceased to ask
for since the adoption by the (U.N.) Security Council of the
Sahnoun plan -- a cease-fire is not rapidly concluded in Zaire,
the international community should envisage the establishment of
an international device of humanitarian security provision," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Sahnoun, the special envoy of the United Nations and
the Organization of African Unity for the Great Lakes region, has
drafted a five-point peace plan calling for the immediate ending
of hostilities in eastern Zaire and the withdrawal of all foreign
troops, including mercenaries, from Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to assume our responsibilities and we ask our
partners about their own availability and about their intentions
of participation, because faced with such a disaster, the action
of the international community should be a concrete action," said
Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He said that France continues to provide total and entire
support to the peace mission of Sahnoun, and expects all those
"who have an influence on the rebels and those who support them"
to "exert this influence with conviction and firmness to lead with
the shortest delay to the cessation of fightings, the withdrawal
of foreign forces and political dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Ministry said earlier that there is no
problem for France to open an air bridge to the Zairean city of
Kisangani to provide humanitarian aid to the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) quoted a source of the ministry
as saying that for months, planes carrying humanitarian cargos
have been able to land in Kisangani and that "they were always
doing that."
</P>
<P>
A French Iliouchine-76 cargo plane carrying 30 tons of
humanitarian aid landed at an old military airbase of Kisangani
Tuesday, AFP quoted a spokesman of the United Nations World Food
Program as saying in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The French Foreign Ministry also said that the United States
has also agreed that "the present situation in Zaire is
unacceptable and that the fighting should stop as quickly as
possible." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
