<HEADLINE> Negotiation Team Stranded, Troops Building Up in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian government troops
are building up around Anlong Veng in northwestern Cambodia while
a government negotiating team with the Khmer Rouge failed to come
back from there.
</P>
<P>
"I refuse now to talk with the people in Anlong Veng any more
unless all my people return safe and sound," First Prime Minister
Norodom Ranariddh told reporters at a ceremony to launch an
Olympic Stadium renovation project today.
</P>
<P>
"Neak Bun Chhay (first deputy chief of general staff) and Tom
Som Bol (Ranariddh's military advisor) checked with (people) in
Anlong Veng and they told us through telephone that all the people
are right, not only alive but also in good health," Ranariddh said.
</P>
<P>
The government says it was able to maintain periodic contact
with the team by radio and telephone.
</P>
<P>
"Neak Bun Chhay will be flying to Thailand in two days to ask
for Thai assistance and to have direct talks with people in Anlong
Veng," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member government negotiating team was helicoptered into
Anlong Veng in February for negotiations with the Khmer Rouge and
has since been stranded there for nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think it is necessary to launch any dry season
offensive. I don't want to talk about fighting anymore," although
"it is true that the Royal Cambodian Armed Forces have moved
troops close to Anlong Veng," Ranariddh said.
</P>
<P>
The first prime minister, who was watching an air show at the
Pochentong Military Airbase in the capital, said the government
"has no plan to use force against Anlong Veng."
</P>
<P>
Local press reported that the government has advanced its
troops to the Khmer Rouge-controlled areas and government military
leaders threatened to break off negotiations with the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
Military officials were quoted as saying that more than
1,000-strong government troops Monday marched into the far
northern province of Preah Vihear, and artillery and ammunition
were flown to a remote government military base near the Thai
border.
</P>
<P>
Ek Sereywath, secretary of state of the Defense Ministry
Wednesday said that the government planned to move some
9,000-strong troops to Preah Vihear to put military pressure on
the Khmer Rouge in Anlong Veng
</P>
<P>
"We have asked them to release our team, but they refused," Ek
Sereywath said.
</P>
<P>
He said military leaders are discussing the possibility of an
attack to encourage more defections from the Khmer Rouge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
