<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Retail Sales Up by 0.8 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. retail sales rose by 0.8
percent in February, about half of the advance in January, the
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that retail sales totaled a seasonally
adjusted 213.2 billion dollars last month, up from 211.5 billion
in January.
</P>
<P>
The latest report was in line with the results of a U.S.
Federal Reserve survey released Wednesday. It said that regional
"economies continue to expand at a relatively moderate pace" with
few signs of mounting inflation.
</P>
<P>
The department also sharply revised January's increase of sales
up to 1.5 percent from the initial estimated 0.6 percent. The
advance was the steepest since February of 1996 when the U.S.
retail sales rose by 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales represent about one-third of the U.S. economic
activities.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Commerce Department said sales of durable goods --
items expected to last more than three years -- rose by 1.6
percent in February, steepest since a 3.1 percent gain in February
1996.
</P>
<P>
Auto dealers posted a 1.7 percent gain, slightly below the 1.9
percent advance in January. Sales of building materials, hardware
and garden supplies shot up by 2.2 percent, even higher than the
strong 1.6 percent jump in January.
</P>
<P>
Demand for nondurable goods such as food and fuel edged up 0.2
percent, much slower than the 1.5 percent advance in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
