<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Unemployment Rate Stays At 10.8 Percent in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
seasonally-adjusted unemployment rate was 10.8 percent in January,
the same as in the last three months of 1996, the EU's statistics
office Eurostat reported today.
</P>
<P>
In January, Luxembourg had the lowest unemployment rate of 3.4
percent, followed by Austria with 4.1 percent. The highest
unemployment was in Spain at 21.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat estimates that 18.1 million people were unemployed in
the EU in January.
</P>
<P>
It says the apparent lack of change in unemployment situation
over the last two years is due to compensating trends.
</P>
<P>
First, a small fall for women from 12.6 percent in January 1995
to 12.4 in January this year was cancelled out by a slight rise
for men from 9.5 percent to 9.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, there were contrasting developments in the EU's 15
member states. Big rises in Germany, Sweden and France were
balanced by regular falls elsewhere, particularly in Britain,
Finland and Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Data from Eurostat also showed that the number of employed
people in the EU continued to rise moderately in the third quarter
of last year -- up 0.4 percent over the same period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The rise was particularly marked in Austria (2.5 percent),
Luxembourg (2.5 percent) and Spain (3.2 percent). Germany and
Sweden were the only member states to record a fall in
employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
