<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Wants to Join in Malaysia' MSC Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 13 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand today expressed
its desire to be among the major players in the development of
Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC).
</P>
<P>
Its Science and Technology and Research Minister Maurice
Williamson said here that his country would encourage more New
Zealand companies to be set up within the MSC.
</P>
<P>
"I think the MSC has got very significant future applications
to a number of nations including New Zealand in particular and we
are going to be a major participant in it," he told reporters
after meeting his Malaysian counterpart Law Hieng Ding.
</P>
<P>
Many New Zealand companies are involved in developing world
class products and services in telecommunications, he said,
adding that working within the MSC will be a very logical
extension of the business that they are involved in.
</P>
<P>
Williamson, who arrived here earlier in the day heading a
15-member delegation for a three-day visit, was briefed by
Multimedia Development Corporation (MDC) officials on the
development of the MSC here.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's Televox International Ltd is scheduled to sign a
joint- venture agreement during the visit with Malaysia's
newly-formed company Quantum Frontier (M) Private Ltd. to become
the first company from New Zealand to hold an MSC status.
</P>
<P>
"Televox, a leading edge company in information technology,
will only be the first of many other New Zealand companies which
will take part in the MSC," Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
An inaugural Joint Commission Meeting on Scientific and
Technological Cooperation is expected to be held during the visit
between the Malaysian and New Zealand delegations to take stock of
progress of the cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Law said Malaysia would enhance cooperation with New Zealand in
the fields of information technology, biotechnology, advanced
material technology and environment technology.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia could also benefit from New Zealand in the
fields of forestry research, landscaping and the use of satellites
for marine resources management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
