<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's 1996 Economy Grows 3.6 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese economy grew 3.6
percent in calender 1996 thanks to expanding private housing
investment and corporate capital investment, the government said
today.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in five years that Japan's real, or
inflation-adjusted, gross domestic product (GDP) posted the 3
percent level growth rate from the year before.
</P>
<P>
The annual GDP growth was 1.4 percent in 1995, 0.6 percent in
1994 and 0.3 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The 3.6 percent growth for 1996 is the highest growth rate
since 1991 when the GDP attained 3.8 percent growth, the Economic
Planning Agency (EPA) said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
It was also the highest among developed countries around the
world in 1996, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
EPA Vice Minister Shimpei Nukaya expressed confidence in the
future course of the economy, saying the nation will certainly
attain the government's target growth of 2.5 percent for fiscal
1996 ending March 31 even if GDP growth for the first quarter of
1997 posts a quarter-to-quarter fall of 0.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
Private-sector economists, however, remain cautious, saying the
data seen to be "too good" considering Japan's current economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
Japan's real GDP grew preliminary 1.0 percent in the
October-December quarter from the previous quarter for
an annualized rate of 3.9 percent, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The growth followed a revised annual growth rate of 1.3 percent
in the July-September period, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
