<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Chancellor Agrees to Slower Cuts in Coal Subsidies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Helmut Kohl agreed
in compromise today to phase out federal subsidy cuts for the
unprofitable coal mining industry in western Germany at a slower
pace following talks with trade union leader Hans Berger.
</P>
<P>
"We have achieved the most important (goals)," said Berger,
head of the trade union IG Bergbau.
</P>
<P>
Friedrish Bohl, Kohl's chief staff, said the step-by-step coal
subsidy cuts will not be as deep as originally planned. However,
he stressed that Bonn will still cut its annual coal subsidies to
5.5 billion marks (about 3.2 billion U.S. dollars) by 2005 from
the current 10 billion marks (about 5.88 billion dollars) as
previously planned.
</P>
<P>
The deal was hammered out after coal miners staged three-day
protests at the government district in Bonn over the subsidy cuts
plan, which was believed to result in the loss of at least 55,000
of 85,000 jobs at mines.
</P>
<P>
The miners demanded 6.5 billion marks (about 3.82 billion
dollars) in annual subsidies by 2005, and said they were willing
to reduce the workforce to 45,000.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Bonn will pay an extra 1.65 billion marks
(about 0.97 billion dollars) through 2005, raising planned annual
subsidies by about 300 million marks (about 176.5 million dollars)
through 2000. The improved medium-term offer is believed to have
helped ease unemployment in the major coal producing areas of the
Ruhr Valley and Saarland.
</P>
<P>
Wolfgang Clement, economic minister of coal-mining state of
North Rhine-Westphalia, said this settlement will lead to four
mines' closure instead of seven by 2000.
</P>
<P>
German Economic Minister Guenter Rexrodt estimated that the
agreement will save half of the 85,000 jobs at mines.
</P>
<P>
In the accord, North Rhine-Westphalia, along with coal-producer
Ruhrkohle AG, pledged to offer 1.75 billion marks (about 1 billion
dollars) in additional subsidies through 2005.
</P>
<P>
Of the continuing annual subsidies from 2005, 4.15 billion
marks (about 2.44 billion dollars) will be paid by Bonn, 1.15
billion (about 680 million dollars) by North Rhine-Westphalia and
200 million (about 117.6 million dollars) by corporates.
</P>
<P>
Some 8,000 protesting miners, who Wednesday lifted the
three-day blockade of the main road at Bonn's government district
and withdrew to nearby Cologne, cautiously accepted today's
agreement. They had threatened to come back if the government
failed to make concessions.
</P>
<P>
However, some miners in the Ruhr Valley were disappointed at
the results and vowed to march to Bonn.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the bituminous coal mines in the west of Germany
received a record handout of 11.2 billion marks (about 6.59
billion dollars) from the state, with 10 billion (about 5.88
billion dollars) from Bonn and the rest from North
Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
German bituminous coal costs 280 marks (about 165 dollars) per
ton, compared with 80 marks (about 47 dollars) per ton for the
same kind purchased on world markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
