<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Credit Card Delinquencies in US Hit All-Time High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The credit card delinquencies
in the U.S. jumped at the end of 1996 to the highest level on
record despite a healthy U.S. economy and low unemployment, the
American Bankers Association (ABA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The delinquency rate -- the percentage of accounts 30 or more
days overdue -- climbed to a seasonally adjusted 3.72 percent of
accounts in the fourth quarter, up from 3.48 percent in the third
quarter, the ABA said in a report.
</P>
<P>
That beat the old record of 3.66 percent set in the second
quarter of last year and was the highest since the ABA began
tracking the figure in 1973.
</P>
<P>
The latest report returns the U.S. credit card delinquencies to
the steady upward trend that they've been on for two years. The
delinquencies posed a decline in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
The increasing credit card delinquencies have coincided with a
mushrooming number of personal bankruptcies in the U.S. which
topped 1 million last year.
</P>
<P>
Economists view the rising consumer debt as one of the chief
risks to U.S. economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
