<HEADLINE> Russia-NATO Ties to Dominate Primakov's Washington Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov's forthcoming visit to Washington will focus on the
relations between Russia and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Tarasov
told a news briefing today.
</P>
<P>
Primakov will leave for Washington on Saturday to pave the way
for the summit between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
U.S. President Bill Clinton on March 20-21 in Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
Stressing Russia's opposition to NATO's eastward expansion,
Tarasov said that Russia made frequent consultations with NATO
Secretary-General Javier Solana recently in order to find a
solution to ensure Russia's security and other interests.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Washington, Primakov is scheduled to meet
with President Clinton before holding wide-range talks with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also hold talks on reduction of strategic
weapons with the United States, Tarasov said, stressing that the
1972 treaty on the limitation of anti-ballistic missile systems
must be taken into account in order to reach a new agreement.
</P>
