<HEADLINE> Uzbekistan Not to Join Any Military Alliance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Uzbek Foreign Minister Abdulaziz
Kamilov said that his country will not join any military or
military-political alliances, Interfax news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with NATO secretary-general Javier Solana in
Tashkent, Kamilov said Uzbekistan has just passed a law on foreign
relations, which stipulates that the country will never become a
member of any military or military-political alliances.
</P>
<P>
However, the Uzbek foreign minister stressed that his country
is ready to cooperate with all security organizations including
NATO.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that NATO had already begun to reform its
institutions to adapt itself to the current situation.
</P>
<P>
NATO wanted to establish a new type of partnership, which will
serve as the broad basis for cooperation with countries outside
the bloc, he added.
</P>
<P>
Solana arrived in Uzbekistan on March 12. He is expected to
hold talks with both President Islam Karimov and Defense Minister
Rustam Akhmedov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
