<HEADLINE> WEU Considers Intervening in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Parliamentary Assembly of the
Western European Union, which concluded a three-day conference in
Athens today, said it would consider intervening in Albania, even
militarily, if civil strife broke out in that country.
</P>
<P>
"The security in the Balkans is at stake, it is inevitable that
the European defense organization will be activated," WEU
Parliamentary Assembly President Luis Maria De Puig and head of
the Greek representation to the organization Constantinos Vrettos
told a press conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
They said the WEU has decided for the timely consideration of
the issue of taking appropriate measures in the possibility of
civil war breaking out in Albania, "especially following strong
criticism regarding lack of similar preparations in the case of
Bosnia."
</P>
<P>
The form of a WEU intervention in Albania, if the country
plunges into civil strife, will also be considered at WEU council
level.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a dispatch by the semi-official Athens
News Agency from Tirana today, representatives of Albania's
political parties today held a meeting chaired by Albanian
President Sali Berisha and decided to call on the WEU to impose
constitutional order in the country.
</P>
<P>
During the three-day WEU conference, participants also focused
on the future of the organization in view of the expected
enlargement of both NATO and the WEU.
</P>
<P>
The conference endorsed a resolution this afternoon forbidding
entry to the organization to all countries failing to gain
accession to either NATO or the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
