<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Defense Minister Calls for Restraint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai today called for exercising restraint following
the shooting incident near the Israeli-Jordanian border which
killed seven Israeli school-girls.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian soldier fired his automatic rifle from an
observation tower at a group of Israeli school girls from Beit
Shemesh, west of Jerusalem, who were on school outing in the
scenic Naharayim area on the Jordanian side of the northern part
of Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
Seven of the girls were killed, including two on the spot and
five others in a local Jordanian hospital, and six others were
wounded in the shooting spree. The Jordanian soldier emptied his
magazine of bullets before he was overpowered by fellow
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The tragic incident, the first of its kind along the
relatively calm Israeli-Jordanian border, shocked and griped
Israel in deep grief. Televisions and radios quickly interrupted
normal broadcasts to break the news.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government swiftly and strongly condemned the
shooting, saying it was an unacceptable act of violence. Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu said nothing could legitimatize
violence, because "there is no greater danger (than violence) to
the peace process." He urged the Jordanian government to bring
those guilty to trial and to fully investigate this incident.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Mordechai and other senior army officers
immediately toured the site. Speaking to reporters, Mordechai
called on all parties to exercise restraint following the
incident.
</P>
<P>
"What's needed to everybody is to be careful ... every
thinking and doing may be threat to the future. It needs now
everybody to be careful, and to look forward, and not to damage
the situation... and to continue the peace process," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government acted quickly to condemn this incident,
while promising to bring the guilty to justice.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein immediately decided to delay his visit to the
United States and return home from Spain to deal with the
situation. He also telephoned Israeli President Ezer Weizman to
express shock and sorrow over the killing and offer his
condolences to families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan also flew to the site of
shooting this afternoon. Calling today as a "black day" for
Jordan, he condemned the incident as an act of "crime and
murder" and a "shame" for Jordanian people. He promised there
would be a full investigation with full knowledge of the Israeli
police and "justice will be deserved."
</P>
<P>
Naharayim, the scenic enclave in the Jordan Valley which was
returned to Jordan by Israel under the 1994 peace treaty, has
been leased to Israel and is a favorite site for Israeli
tourists. Ironically, the area has been called "Island of
Peace."
</P>
<P>
Today's incident also occurred during a time of rising
tension between the two countries and is expected to have
negative implications on bilateral ties. Referring to the recent
accusations by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), Jordan
and other Arab countries, Netanyahu warned that "we cannot
pursue peace unless we pursue peacefully."
</P>
<P>
In stronger terms, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy blamed
today's shooting on the recent harsh statements made by King
Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Days ago, Hussein wrote a letter to Netanyahu, criticizing
the latter's policies for creating the current
Israeli-Palestinian peace deadlock and warning this would lead to
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israel Radio, Levy said today's shooting was the
result of the recent warning of violence over the deadlock in
peace process. He requested the Jordanian government to ensure
that harsh comments would not be translated into tragic incident
such as today's.
</P>
<P>
Levy also warned the Palestinian side to be careful in their
accusations of Israel, saying today's incident showed that
threat of violence would take the form of tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister Office said that senior Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat had phoned Netanyahu to express sorrow
and condolences over the shooting, though there had been no word
from PNA President Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
