<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Reaffirm Commitment to Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany have shrugged
off rumors and doubts over their capability to keep the timetable
for the launching of the future European single currency, euro,
and reaffirmed their determination to create the monetary union on
January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
French Minister of Economy and Finance Jean Arthuis and his
German counterpart, Theo Waigel, gave the message at the meeting
of the Franco-German Economic and Financial Council held Wednesday
in Lyon, which was also attended by Governor of the Bank of France
Claude Trichet and President of the Bundesbank Hans Tietmeyer.
</P>
<P>
The economic and financial leaders of France and Germany
expressed optimism over their governments' capability to observe
the criteria of the Maastricht treaty for participating in the
monetary union and to maintain the calendar made by the European
Council.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have any doubt on that point," said Waigel, who
described all other speculations as "pointless."
</P>
<P>
French and German officials based their optimism on the sign of
resumption of growth of their economies, which is predicted at 2.5
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The European Union will decide in the first six months of 1998
which countries can join the monetary union on the basis of their
economic performance and financial situation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Arthuis said that France, as Germany, is attached "in an
intangible way to the principle of independence of the (future)
European Central Bank," while the role of the future Council of
Monetary Stability of the monetary union is limited to
coordinating monetary policies of countries within the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The idea of setting up a stability council for the euro was
initiated by France but met with a lukewarm reception from
Germany, which fears that it will jeopardize the independence of
the future European Central Bank to be responsible for the issuing
of the euro bills.
</P>
<P>
Arthuis said that such a council will bring no harm to either
the independence of the future central bank or the principle of
subsidiariness for the role of the council itself.
</P>
<P>
He said that such a council will only work for the assurance of
convergence of economic policies of countries of the euro zone and
their observation of the engagements made in the Pact of Stability
and Growth of the monetary union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
