<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Gets US Word of Objection to Jewish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt said today Washington has
assured that there has been no change in the U.S. position
opposing any preemptive attempt on East Jerusalem before the
Israeli-Palestinian talks start to determine the final status of
the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to "Good Morning Egypt" T.V. program from Washington
today, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's Political Adviser Ossama
el-Baz said that the U.S. remained committed to its pledges to the
parties concerned, as a sponsor of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has assured Mubarak that he opposes
Israeli settlement activity and the imposition of a fait accompli
in Jerusalem as his predecessors always did.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak launched a five-day visit to the U.S. last Friday to
sound out the U.S. leadership on the peace process amid mounting
Arab rage over the recent Israeli decision to build 6,500 Jewish
homes and close four Palestinian offices in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs are also dissatisfied with Israel's projected withdraw
from only 9 percent of the rural West Bank as the first step of
the three-stage pullbacks.
</P>
<P>
"He was keen to know whether Washington had changed its
position in regard to the land for peace principle and he was told
by Clinton that U.S. did not change its stand in opposing the
Israeli settlement policy," said the Egyptian official.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a strong advocate of the Arab cause, was the first Arab
country to make peace with Israel in 1979, but bilateral ties
remain cool. Both countries are major beneficiaries of the
U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
Baz, reiterating Egypt's stand, accused Israel of trying to
impose a fait accompli on the Holy City regardless of the signed
agreements with the Palestinians, "as if it was acting alone in a
remote island and was politically and diplomatically isolated from
the world."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, on the eve of his meeting with Clinton on Monday,
deplored the U.S. veto of a U.N. Security Council draft resolution
calling on Israel to halt the settlement activities, which he said
had prompted a "feeling of injustice" and cast doubt about the
"credibility of U.S. as a fair mediator" in the Middle East peace
march.
</P>
<P>
It was "unfortunate the resolution was not adopted, because it
could have given a signal to the Israelis to stop any settlement
activity, especially in the area of Jerusalem," he lamented.
</P>
<P>
At a joint conference with Mubarak held after the talks,
Clinton said that, despite the veto, U.S. does not agree with
Israel's decision but it was deterred by the wording of the
resolution which smells of precluding the Jerusalem issue from
final talks set to start this month.
</P>
<P>
What the United States is trying to do, he said, is to reach a
point "where the parties themselves can honestly make a fair, just
and lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
The U.S., co-sponsor of the peace process and Israel's biggest
ally, had joined the international chorus to criticize the Israeli
housing plan before it vetoed the draft U.N. resolution, supported
by other 14 members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
According to Egyptian officials, Mubarak has urged the Clinton
administration to play the role of a fair mediator and create an
atmosphere of Arab-Israeli confidence towards the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Information Minister Safwat al-Sherif said today that
during meetings with Clinton and other U.S. decision-makers,
Mubarak has played up the dangers posed by the Israeli settlements
in East Jerusalem to regional peace.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have decided to attend Saturday's
international conference in Gaza City, along with diplomats from
Russia, the EU, Japan, Norway and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Infuriated and humiliated by the several Israeli decisions this
month, Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
called the meeting "to save the peace process" which he said is
"in a real crisis." 
</P>
</TEXT>
