<HEADLINE> British Soldier Injured in Northern Irish Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- A British soldier was injured in
an explosion in north Belfast of Northern Ireland today.
</P>
<P>
When suspected IRA guerrillas ambushed a patrol vehicle, "we
have one soldier slightly injured," Reuter quoted a police source
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said they thought a home-made mortar or
grenade of a type used by the Irish Republican Army (IRA) had been
fired at a military patrol in the Ardoyne district, according to
Reuter.
</P>
<P>
A week ago troops narrowly escaped serious injury when a bomb
exploded behind a wall in nationalist Ballymurphy, a sprawling
housing estate in the west of the city.
</P>
<P>
The IRA, which shattered a fragile peace process by abandoning
a 17-month truce a year ago, said recently that it was unlikely to
consider another cease-fire until after a British election due by
May 22. 
