<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Biotech Companies in UK Grow Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Britain's biotechnology industry
is growing rapidly as the number of companies in the sector
looking for new drugs has more than doubled in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Employment in the sector has also doubled, but the numbers are
still too low to have a significant impact on unemployment,
according to a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
However, the report by Arthur Andersen, the accountant and
management consultant, warned that the sector's continued growth
depends on finding at least 1 billion pounds (1.6 billion US
dollars) of funding in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
Britain's biotechnology industry also faces uncertainty over
European Union patent laws for biotechnology, which are now under
review.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, there were 221 UK biotech companies
employing 10,590 people in 1996. Their total revenue was 700
million pounds (1.12 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The figures are up by a third on 1994, and are expected to grow
by a further third by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Drug researchers are the biggest group, with 78 companies
employing 4,870 people. In terms of performance, these "can match
those in the US biotech sector," the report said. By market value,
the five biggest UK companies match some of those in the US top
20, it added.
</P>
<P>
The biggest UK companies are British Biotech, Celltech and
Chiroscience. The three raised 1.1 billion pounds (1.76 billion US
dollars) from investors in the 18 months to December 1996.
</P>
<P>
The sector's growth is the result of several factors:
</P>
<P>
-- Easier access to capital through venture capital funds,
changes in stock exchange listing rules, the creation of the
Alternative Investment Market;
</P>
<P>
-- Greater government commitment to biotech through grants and
awareness-raising programs;
</P>
<P>
-- Better links between academic and commercial science;
</P>
<P>
-- Greater outsourcing of research by pharmaceuticals
companies;
</P>
<P>
-- The creation of the London-based European Medicines
Evaluation Agency, through which drugs can be approved for the
whole of the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
