<HEADLINE> Arafat Blasts Israeli Government's Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat today blasted a recent Israeli government
decision on building Jewish settlements in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"The (Israel's) decision (on Har Homa) is intended to blow up
the peace process, but we don't accept that," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service
based in East Jerusalem, Arafat made the statement when he was
addressing an emergency session of the 88-member Palestinian
Council held in the West Bank city of Bethlehem at a time when
tensions are running high between the Israelis and the
Palestinians as a result of Israel's decision to build the new
settlement at Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"This Israeli settlement plan was submitted to (the late
Prime Minister Yitzhak) Rabin, he refused to deal with it.
It was also submitted to (former Prime Minister Shimon) Peres
and he refused to deal with it," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
"Yet, the new government comes to deal with the plan with all
of its insolence and in a blatant challenge to Arabs, Christians,
 Moslems and Palestinians," he added.
</P>
<P>
"With their decisions, they (the Netanyahu government) say no
to peace, no to peace not only with the Palestinians, but
also with Arabs and the entire Middle East," said Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader said: "I am sorry that the U.S.
veto was against 14 countries (in the Security Council) and
against an international unanimity. Yet, President (Bill) Clinton
made it clear to (Egyptian President Hosni) Mubarak while
speaking to journalists that this doesn't mean that the U.S.
agrees on the settlement policy."
</P>
<P>
"Thank God, all invited countries responded positively to our
call for a Saturday meeting (in Gaza). Some friends suggested
inviting Israel to the meeting, but I didn't," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said: "Settlement beasts will not only swallow the
Palestinian lands, but the entire peace process."
</P>
<P>
"If he (Netanyahu) wants to devour the peace process the issue
is left for the international community to decide on whether to
choose peace or to surrender," Arafat noted. "When we went to
Madrid, we were relying on the land-for-peace formula and not on
land-for-surrender, or land-for-settlements."
</P>
<P>
Arafat appealed to the Israeli peace forces, who in the
Knesset approved the Hebron Protocol with a majority of 87
votes, to save the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
