<HEADLINE> Conservative MPs Demand Report Leak Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- British Conservative MPs are
calling for an inquiry into the leaking of a Commons report
criticizing the government's proposed nursery voucher scheme,
which should be published next week.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, parents of all four-year-old children in
England and Wales will be given vouchers worth 1,100 pounds (1,760
US dollars) to use for nursery school education.
</P>
<P>
But the report from the Conservative-dominated Commons
education and employment select committee said it is unlikely to
increase parental choice, raise standards or even provide extra
places for children.
</P>
<P>
The report leaked Wednesday said the main problem with the
scheme is that it has led to more four-year-olds being recruited
into reception classes by schools anxious to safeguard pupil
numbers and funding. Parental choice would not be enhanced if
schools took more pupils to the detriment of nurseries and play
groups.
</P>
<P>
British Schools Minister Robin Squire has refected the
criticism and told BBC Radio today that the scheme has led to an
increase in parental choice and higher standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
