<HEADLINE> UK New Car Sales Rise 2.4 Pct in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- New car sales growth in Britain
slowed down considerably last month compared with January, with
lack of interest from private buyers rekindling concern in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from the Society of Motor Manufacturers
and Traders (SMMT), new car sales in February were at 162,887, 2.4
percent higher than the 159,013 units in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
This was sharply lower compared with the more than 9 percent
year-on-year growth recorded in January, the SMMT said.
</P>
<P>
However, as a result, sales for the first two months of this
year as a whole rose 5.4 percent to 369.671, compared with 350,774
in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The share taken by private buyers fell to 42 percent last month
from 43 percent in the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there was also a further significant rise in the
market share taken by imports, which accounted for 65.4 percent of
last month's market, up from 62.4 percent in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the industry was not much concerned over the increased
import share as this was being substantially offset by rising UK
car production for export. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
