<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Rate Doubles for UK Young Drinkers: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The death rate from
alcohol-related diseases in Britain's young people aged 15 to 44
has doubled in 10 years time, according to an official health
report to be published next month.
</P>
<P>
The report by the Office for National Statistics will show that
although the numbers are still relatively small, deaths in young
men from alcoholic diseases went up from one in 100,000 to two
between 1984 to 1994, and in young women from 0.5 per 100,000 to
one.
</P>
<P>
The total of alcohol-related deaths in England and Wales went
up from 4,124 in 1985 to 5,617 in 1994, a rise of more than 36
percent, the report, The Health of Adult Britain, will point out.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey found that children in Britain are starting to
drink alcohol younger and that some are drinking large quantities,
which have made doctors become increasingly concerned.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to figures from the Health Education
Authority, three quarters of 11-year-olds have tried alcohol and
70 percent of 11- to 16-year-olds said they drank "quite a lot"
and believed that life was more fun after a drink. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
