<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls on Donors to Extend Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Disaster
Prevention and Preparedness Commission today called on donors for
emergency food aid in a bid to mitigate food and water scarcity
in the Somali, Oromia and Southern People's regions.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here, the commission said ambassadors and
representatives of donor countries and welfare organizations were
briefed on measures so far taken to address the natural disaster in
those areas.
</P>
<P>
The commission said so far it has dispatched relief food,
water tank trucks, tankers, heavy duty trucks in addition to
financial assistance to alleviate the problem, adding that
a team had been deployed to the areas to study the magnitude of the
problems, particularly the shortage of water.
</P>
<P>
The commission said it made the call as the relief aid
dispatched to the areas was insufficient to address the existing
problems owing to extent of the natural disaster in the drought
affected areas.
</P>
<P>
It called on humanitarian organizations to support efforts being
made by pertinent government bodies in addressing health problems in
these areas.
</P>
<P>
According to local reports, about 600,000 persons in the Somali
region, 386,200 persons in Borena and Bale zones of the Oromia region,
and 18,000 persons in South Omo zone of the Southern People's region
have been hit by drought and need relief aid. enditem

