<HEADLINE> Salim Nominated to Contest for OAU Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has nominated the
incumbent OAU Secretary General, Slaim Ahmed Salim, to contest for the
post for a third consecutive term, Minister of Foreign Affairs and
International Co-operation Jakaya Kikwete said today.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Daily News, Kikwete told reporters here
that President Benjamin Mkapa has written letters to other African
heads of states to seek their support in re-electing Salim whose term
expires in next June.
</P>
<P>
He expressed optimism that Salim will be re-elected to the post for
a third consecutive term in a meeting scheduled to be held in
Harare, Zimbabwe in June, this year. If he wins he will lead the
organisation for four years more.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister told reporters that the OAU member heads of
state are expected to meet in Lome, Togo on March 26 to discuss and
find ways of resolving the eastern Zaire conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision to convene the summit was reached in Tripol,
Libya recently where OAU member countries' ministers held their 65th
general meeting to discuss issues facing the continent.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete said the Central Organ for Conflict Prevention, Management
and Resoltuion meeting will be preceded by a meeting of member
countries' ministers.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister further said the ministers were not satisfied
with conflict resolvance efforts in eastern Zaire, but were impressed
by achievements made in other countries facing internal conflicts.
</P>
<P>
He said there were progress in resolving conflicts in central
Africa, countries in western Sahara, Angola, Sierra Leone and Liberia,
and appealed to the international community to extend economic support
to enable them to survive while solving their problems.
</P>
<P>
Kikwete said a peace enforcing army drawn from Gabon, Burkina
Faso, Chad, Mali, Togo and Senegal has already started work in central
Africa, while Morocco and Polisario have started discussing
peace measures for the west Saharan conflicting countries.
</P>
<P>
In Sierra Leone, Kikwete said, peace keeping army has not started
work due to disagreement on the size of the army with the government
proposing a 700-man team while the rebels are for about 50 to 70
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
On Burundi conflict, Kikwete said the meeting maintained that
economic sanctions will continue untill the Pierre Buyoya
government implement conditions given in the Arusha meeting last
July. enditem

