<HEADLINE> Egypt's Delegate to Attend Gaza Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's Assistant Foreign Minister
for Arab Affairs Badr Hamam will leave here tomorrow for Gaza to
attend an emergency conference to be held Saturday aimed to save
the peace process from collapse, the Egyptian MENA news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Humiliated and frustrated by Israeli decision to build Jewish
settlement in Har Homa in East Jerusalem, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat Tuesday invited diplomats from the U.S., Russia, the
European Union, Egypt, Japan, Norway and Jordan to the Gaza
conference in a bid to set the peace march moving.
</P>
<P>
Israel, however, refused to attend the meeting on grounds that
such a gathering violated the autonomy agreements which stipulate
that disputes between Israel and Palestine must be resolved in a
way agreed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Palestine's delegate to the Arab League Mohamed Sobeih said
today the Gaza meeting aims at getting all countries involved in
the Oslo agreements acquainted with the "perils of Israel's
violations."
</P>
<P>
Sobeih declined to comment on whether the Gaza meeting would
issue a statement to urge Israel to halt the building of the
settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But he said the Israeli government had to backtrack on such a
wrong step because the letters of guarantees affiliated in the
Oslo stipulate that religious and cultural institutions in
Jerusalem be kept intact.
</P>
<P>
"Israeli leaders should realize that changing the holy city's
status is absolutely unacceptable to the Palestinians," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai have made clear that Israel would not
back down from its recent decisions that fueled the Arab rage.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the peace process, has been a strong
advocate of the Palestinian cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
