<HEADLINE> Killer of 7 Israeli Students Arrested in Jordan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The man who killed seven Israeli
students and wounded several others earlier today on the
Jordanian-Israeli border has been arrested.
</P>
<P>
The killer was identified as Ahammad Musa, a 26-year-old driver
serving in the Jordanian army, officials close to the case said.
He reportedly took a gun from one of his friends to carry out the
shooting, but the motive behind the killing was not known for the
time being.
</P>
<P>
After the killing took place, King Hussein telephoned Israeli
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and condemned the shooting
incident near the Israel-Jordan border.
</P>
<P>
The king, who is on an official visit to London, also offered
his condolences to families of the victims, Jordan's Petra news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Musa opened fire at a van carrying Israeli school girls in the
northwestern town of Bahulha town in the Naharayim area near the
Israeli-Jordanian border, which has been relatively calm since the
two sides signed a peace treaty in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Naharayim is an scenic enclave in the Jordan Valley which was
returned to Jordan by Israel under the 1994 peace treaty, but
Israelis still have full access to the area for sightseeings.
</P>
<P>
Hussein, after calling Netanyahu, decided to delay his visit to
the United States scheduled on March 18 and come back from London
to settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan and Prime Minister Abdul Karim
Kabariti also went to the hospital where the injured are treated
and expressed sympathy to them.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian-Israeli relations are in a delicate situation as
Hussein has just sent Netanyahu a tough-worded letter, saying that
the Israeli prime minister's "actions have made peace appear like
mirage."  
</P>
</TEXT>
