<HEADLINE> World Food Program Signs Protocol to Assist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) signed
an understanding protocol with the Angolan government today on
providing the southern African country humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The protocol was signed by Angolan Minister of Assistance and
Social Reinsertion Albino Malungo and WFP Chief in Africa Mohamed
Zejjari, who arrived here Monday for a work visit.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, WFP, the second largest assistance body in
the United Nations, will help Angola settle down its more than
300,000 war refugees, who will begin to return home from May.
</P>
<P>
WFP will also offer aids for restoring social and industrial
infrastructure in Angola's seriously war-damaged areas, said the
protocol.
</P>
<P>
By signing the protocol, WFP becomes the country's biggest aid
provider in 1997 and an estimated 662,000 Angolans will benefit
from the protocol, local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Malungo today also signed with German Ambassador to Angola
Helmut Van Edig an accord under which Germany will provide about
4.2 million U.S. Dollars to help demobilized Angolan servicemen
return to the civil life and get professional training. enditem

