<HEADLINE> Turkish Government Agrees to Curb Fundamentalism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's coalition government
today agreed to implement the recommendations by the National
Security Council (NSC) aimed at curbing the increasing
fundamentalist activities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The decision made at a cabinet meeting, which lasted for nearly
four hours, claimed that the government would make every effort
to fight the threat of "religious extremism " .
</P>
<P>
Public opinion held that the Thursday meeting was crucial since
it could show whether the coalition government has settled their
dispute on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the meeting, Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan unexpectedly told the press that in line with the
constitution, the NSC recommendations would be given the first
place on the agenda, widely seen as a sharp contrast with his
previous attitude.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Tansu Ciller said
at the end of the meeting that the cabinet ministers had
reached a consensus on the strict implementation of the NSC
recommendations designed to defend the secularist system in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, also chairwoman of the junior coalition partner True
Path Party (DYP), said: "These measures will be treated with
strictness. No one should doubt that. Let no one speculate
anyone."
</P>
<P>
The military-dominated NSC meeting was called in February to
discuss ways for pressing the Islamist government to take strong
measures against the increasingly rampant fundamentalist
activities.
</P>
<P>
A 22-Point communique put forward by the NSC meeting
triggered a confrontation between the RP and military in the
past weeks, which had been feared to lead to a nationwide
political crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the pressure by both the military and DYP, Erbakan
finally signed the recommendations on March 5 so as to avoid the
collapse of the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that all the ministers concerned would
start working soon and take practical measures to implement the
NSC decisions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, Erbakan attributed the recent political
turmoil at home to what he called "secularist reactionaries",
saying these people only wanted to impose their own will on
others but did not know religion.
</P>
<P>
Before the signing of the NSC recommendations, he also
vowed that the government was constitutionally responsible for the
Parliament, implying the military was using force to put
pressure on him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
