<HEADLINE> Zambia's Largest University Closes Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The University of Zambia, the
largest in the country, was closed down this afternoon following
a disturbance caused by a boycott of classes.
</P>
<P>
University Registrar Michael Tandeo said here today that all
the students have been ordered to vacate their rooms
immediately and to leave the campus by 17:00 (local time).
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the closure of the university does not
affect its post-graduate programs or the school of medicine.
</P>
<P>
Tandeo said the senate met today and concluded that the
situation can not be allowed to continue as it has serious
implications on the normal activities of the university.
</P>
<P>
Some students said before leaving the university that the
closure is too sudden.
</P>
<P>
The students started a class boycott on Monday, demanding
immediate payment of 280,000 Kwacha (about 215 U.S. Dollars) to
each student as book allowance.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen students have been expelled since then for alleged
rioting causing damage to the institution.
</P>
<P>
The students demand an immediate and unconditional
reinstatement of the expelled students. enditem

