<HEADLINE> Clinton Condemns Shooting of School Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said on Thursday that shooting of seven Israeli school children by
a Jordanian soldier was "an inexcusable and tragic act of
violence,"
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks before his departure for North Carolina. He
said: "There is no justification or excuse for these acts", at a
time of high-tension between the Arabs and Israelis over Israel's
violation of peace agreements by construction of Jewish homes in
east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
But Clinton said there was no evidence that "this terrible
incident is related to the tensions in the area over the issues."
</P>
<P>
"We have no reason to believe that this was politically
motivated by any larger group or anything," he said.
</P>
<P>
Appealing for calm in the region, Clinton said: "There needs to
be a certain mutuality of action in the Middle East to get this
peace process well under way. That is what I had hoped would
happen after the Hebron agreement."
</P>
<P>
Reports from Madrid said King Hussein of Jordan would cut short
his visit in Spain and put off a planned trip to Washington to
discuss with Clinton over over the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian embassy to Spain said on Thursday that King Hussein
had condemned the killing of the school children and would release
a statement later.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also urged Arab and
Israeli leaders to keep calm over the shooting incident.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon all leaders in the region to calm the
situation, to do their utmost to prevent future violence in any
form and to redouble their efforts to forge a just and lasting
peace," she said in a written statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
