<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Current Account Deficit in 1996 Worst in 9 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. current account
deficit soared to 165.1 billion dollars last year, the second
worst performance in history, the U.S. Commerce Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The gain of 11.4 percent in the current account deficit
reflected an increase in the imbalance in goods to an all-time
high and a third straight shortfall in investment earnings.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit is considered the broadest gauge of
the trade performance in the U.S. because it measures not only
trade in goods and services but also investment flows between
countries and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The deficit in 1996 marked the worst performance since a record
high deficit of 167.4 billion dollars in 1987. It was also much
larger than the 148.2 billion imbalance of 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, the deficit in the fourth quarter shrank to 41.4
billion dollars from 47.9 billion in the third.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the merchandise deficit was up by 8.2
percent to a record 187.7 billion dollars last year. Offsetting
those deficit increases, America's surplus in service trade rose
7.5 percent to 73.5 billion, also an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
The investment deficit rose 5 percent to 8.4 billion dollars.
In the final category, which includes U.S. foreign aid payments,
the deficit rose by 21.1 percent to 42.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
The United States was transformed from the world's largest
creditor nation to the largest debtor in 1980s.
</P>
<P>
U.S. economists believe that the U.S. current account deficit
will deteriorate again this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho PM to Step Down Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Prime Minister
Ntsu Mokhehle is to retire from active politics at the end of his
term of office early next year due to ill-health and old age.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle, 79, said in Maseru, the capital of the kingdom
earlier this week that he would not run for party elections or
general elections, reported the South African Press Association
here today.
</P>
<P>
Mokhehle, the leader of the ruling Basotholand Congress Party
(BCP), said that ill-health and old age put him at a
disadvantage, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that I am old and ill. For these and other
personal reasons I agree that I must go," he was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
When asked who should succeed him, Mokhehle said there were
many capable people in the BCP who could replace him.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, Mokhehle's deputy Molapo Qhobela, believed
to be the leader of a faction within the BCP, called for the
resignation of an ailing Mokhehle, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho is a small land-locked kingdom surrounded by South
Africa. enditem

=03132046

=03132053
NNNN
04:51 04:52 g # PAB
</P>
