<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-13 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Marks South Lebanon's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon inaugurated this evening
activities commemorating the first Israeli aggression into this
country on March 14, 1978, the day when Israel took some one tenth
of Lebanon's territories.
</P>
<P>
In a message to his people, Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
accused Israel of treating Lebanon as merely a "field for
settling accounts, crises and solutions."
</P>
<P>
He noted that until now, Israel has not shown its intentions
to implement the U.N. Resolution 425 issued by the Security
Council 19 years ago, which calls for an Israeli withdrawal from
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Compared to a relatively low profile in the past, Lebanon is
determined to hold grand ceremonies this year to mark the Day of
Unity with South Lebanon for it is the first following a 17-day
Israeli blitz against Lebanon in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
Besides the March 14, 1978 aggression, a bombardment by
Israeli forces at a U.N. peacekeeping force camp at Qana on
April 18, 1996, in which more than 100 civilians were killed, is
also marked on the day.
</P>
<P>
According to an agenda issued by the Parliamentarian
Committee for Commemorating March 14 and April 18, candle
marches will be organized in Beirut, the capital of Lebanon, and
other major cities tonight, mosques will shout Allah's name and
churches will sound their bells.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign guests participating in the occasion is
Esmat Abdul-Maguid, Secretary General of the Arab League, who
arrived here this morning particularly for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi underlined that the Lebanese people are believed in
peace and do not believe in violence as a way to respond
aggression.
</P>
<P>
He urged the United States to refrain from using its veto in
the U.N. Security Council on issues pertaining to the
construction of Jewish settlements by Israel in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Representative of the U.S. cast a veto last Friday when the
Security Council was voting on a resolution condemning the
Jewish state for its housing plans in East Jerusalem, prompting
an anger of the Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are upholding a just and comprehensive peace, this is our
decision and we will never deviate from it," Hrawi said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his country's position adhering to an interlock
of the Syrian and Lebanese tracks. "This is our choice," he
said, "and Israel can do nothing to separate the two tracks."
</P>
<P>
Calling for the Israeli withdrawal from the south, the
Lebanese president reasserted that after the withdrawal, the
Lebanese authorities will "guarantee a security" in the
area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
