<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Believes Helsinki Summit to be Most Difficult </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today expressed his worry about the forthcoming talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton, saying it would be the most difficult
one in the history of Russian-American relations.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass news agency, at a meeting with the heads
of the Russian mass media, Yeltsin noted that the questions on
NATO's enlargement, reduction of strategic offensive weapons and
economic relations between the two countries will be the main
topics on the summit agenda.
</P>
<P>
Yelstin said: "I want to put forth several difficult questions
to President Clinton."
</P>
<P>
He is interested, among other things, why Germany, Japan and
other Western countries actively operate on the Russian market,
while the United States is trailing behind.
</P>
<P>
On the problem of NATO enlargement, Yeltsin said that Russia
may disagree with the United States over the NATO issue at the
forthcoming talks in Helsinki. But it should not be dramatized, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said he heard a "call for a compromise" in his recent
telephone conversation with U.S. President Clinton and will agree
to the compromise which would not damage Russia's interests.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-U.S. summit talks is scheduled for 19-21 March in
Helsinki, the capital of of Finland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
