<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> s f s 2286 China-Li Peng-Meeting-2 Li Peng Meets Press (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In reply to a question on China's entry into WTO, Li said that
as a major trading nation in the world, China is eager to join the
WTO, and has made great efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"We have reduced the average import tariff rate to 23 percent
from 35 percent and made the commitment to further cut the rate to
15 percent by the end of the century, about the average level for
developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that China welcomes recent progress in talks on Chinese
accession to the WTO, the premier said, it is abnormal that China
has been unable to join the WTO for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
"Granted that economic interests have played a part in this,
there is no denying that this has also been due to political
factors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I can reiterate on behalf of the Chinese government that,
after joining the WTO, China will fulfil its obligations while
enjoying rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that it is known to all that China is still a
developing country and that it is unacceptable to apply to China
the criteria for developed countries concerning its accession to
the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"China needs the WTO, and the WTO also needs China," he said,
adding that relevant countries should take a sensible attitude so
that the issue will be resolved as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you, however, that China has enough patience to
wait," he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question whether provinces and ministries will
interfere in the affairs of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) after July 1, Li said that HKSAR will be a special
administrative region with a high degree of autonomy by then,
toward which China will adopt the policy of "One country, two
systems" and "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong".
</P>
<P>
Thus, "no provinces and ministries will be allowed to interfere
in HKSAR's affairs," he added.
</P>
<P>
Li went on to note that some people from the British side
claimed recently that they would supervise over the implementation
of the Sino-British Joint Declaration on Hong Kong issue after
July 1.
</P>
<P>
"This is not realistic, as the issue of Hong Kong will be
purely China's internal affair after the country resumes the
exercise of its sovereignty over the region on July 1 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
