<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> s f s 3398 China-Li Peng-Meeting-4 Li Peng Meets Press (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Answering a question on Sino-U.S. relations, Li said, "At my
invitation, Vice-President Al Gore will soon visit China. This
visit will be an important event in relations between China and
the United States."
</P>
<P>
"One of the important tasks for Vice-President Al Gore during
his visit is to prepare for a meeting between the top leaders of
China and US, which will take place later this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While Vice-President Al Gore is in China, we will also
co-chair a forum to discuss environmental protection and
development issues. And we will also have an exchange of views on
other issues of mutual interest," the Chinese Premier said.
</P>
<P>
"Vice-President Al Gore will be accorded a friendly reception
in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is the biggest developing country and the United States
is the most developed country in the world. So our two countries
exercise strong influences in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Owing to differences in ideology resulting from our different
social systems, we have some disagreements. But we have to reduce
confrontation and develop cooperation in order to develop our
relations on a normal track," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining a healthy and stable development of Sino-US
relations will be in the interest of world peace and stability,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"In handling international relations, the Chinese government
always maintains that all countries regardless of their size
should be all treated as equals. And what China opposes most is
interference in other countries' internal affairs. And in this
matter China has been a victim," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since China itself is strongly opposed to interference in
internal affairs from other countries, naturally, China will be
the last country to interfere in or influence the internal affairs
of other countries in any form, he said.
</P>
<P>
Answering the question on Sino-Russian relations, the Premier
said that China will sign a border disarmament agreement with
Russia and three central Asian countries during President Jiang
Zemin's state visit to Russia in coming April.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the reduction of military forces in the border
area will be signed by the heads of states of China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrghyzstan and Tajikistan, said Li.
</P>
<P>
"With the signing of this agreement," the premier pointed out,
"the border that we share with the four countries will be a border
for cooperation and good neighborliness."
</P>
<P>
He added the leaders of China and Russia will exchange views on
the international situation and issue an important political
document during Jiang's visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
He also made a brief explanation on the strategic partnership
for cooperation, established between China and Russia last April,
that is geared toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the fact that China and Russia share a border of
over 4,000 km, he noted China hopes that the two countries will
have a friendly relationship.
</P>
<P>
The premier added that the two economies are "highly
complementary," and that China wishes to develop Sino-Russian
cooperation in economic, trade and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Russia are important countries, Li noted, and
both countries hope to play their roles in facilitating regional
and world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"So, such a strategic partnership for cooperation is not
directed at any third country," the premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
