<HEADLINE> Whereabouts of Albanian President Unknown: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The whereabouts of Albanian
President Sali Berisha are unknown, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported today from southern Albanian town of
Gjirokaster.
</P>
<P>
Berisha's top bodyguard said that whether Berisha will flee the
country depends on development of the domestic situation.
</P>
<P>
ANA reported that the newly-appointed Prime Minister Bashkim
Fino had threatened to resign unless insurgents lay down their
arms by Sunday. He is reportedly asking for military assistance
from the West in order to restore order.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, insurgents in Vlore, Sarande and
Gjirokaster have expressed their support for the new broad-based
government formed by Fino, but have refused to lay down their arms
unless Berisha steps down.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the insurrection, under the umbrella of "National
Committee for the People's Salvation" formed three days ago in
Gjirokaster, are to meet in Vlore.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that there may be a meeting between the leaders
of the movement and Fino, along with OSCE special envoy Franz
Vranitzky and Greek Foreign Undersecretary Yannos Kranidiotis, who
arrived in Albania today on a mediating mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
