<HEADLINE> Clinton Tears Tendon and to Undergo Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
tore a tendon in his knee early today after stumbling on steps at
the home of golf pro Greg Norman in Florida and will undergo
surgery to repair the damage in Washington this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Clinton stumbled on a step as he left Norman's home and tore
his quadriceps tendon. He was taken to a local hospital at West
Palm Beach, southeast Florida and he will fly to Bethesda Naval
Hospital in Washington around noon. His doctor said he had to
undergo a surgery in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's doctors said he will be in a leg brace and crutches
for two weeks to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is due to travel to Helsinki to meet with Russian
President Boris Yeltsin next Wednesday. Despite the injury,
Clinton said the summit will proceed next week.
</P>
<P>
"It will go on, you bet," Clinton told reporters as he was
lifted in a wheelchair onto Air Force One for a flight back to
Washington for knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
The president was in Hobe Sound, Florida, to play in a two-day
tournament sponsored by Norman. He was spending the night at
Norman's 80-acre oceanside estate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
