<HEADLINE> China, Britain Narrow Differences on Hong Kong Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China and Britain have narrowed
their differences on the entry of a limited number of advance
staff of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) into Hong Kong before
July 1, 1997, a Chinese official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news briefing, Chen Zuo'er, Chinese representative
on the JLG, said that the two sides narrowed the differences and
made progress on the matter at the 23rd experts meeting on defense
of the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group (JLG).
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and British experts completed the scheduled agenda
through pragmatic and serious talks over the past two days. "I
hope that news on further progress will be reported at the 39th
JLG meeting to be held in London next week," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations lasted 11 months on the entry of a limited number
of advance PLA staff, who will just make necessary preparations to
help the PLA Hong Kong garrison to fulfill the defense mission
after July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Experts on both sides have discussed the matter for 11 months,
and only three months are left before the handover of the
political power, so time is limited. At this meeting, the two
sides came to realize that time is pressing," said the Chinese
representative.
</P>
<P>
Chen continued, "The transfer of defense is the common
responsibility of both Chinese and British sides, and we should
eliminate obstacles and quicken steps."
</P>
<P>
Alan Paul, who headed the British experts team, said that the
two-day discussions were pragmatic, thorough and seriously minded.
"Both sides have a much better understanding of each other's
concerns. We examined all the issues, including the highly
technical ones. This will certainly be helpful in taking forward
these discussions in the course of the JLG meeting next week in
London," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
