<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV Cases on Rise in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of people infected with
HIV virus in Vietnam is growing by about 1,000 a year, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
As many as 4,811 people have been tested HIV positive and
another 618 have developed full-blown AIDS since 1991 when the
first case of the disease was found in the country.
</P>
<P>
The report said 373 people had died of AIDS or AIDS-related
complications in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Roughly half of Vietnam's HIV cases were found in Ho Chi Minh
City in the south.
</P>
<P>
Men account for over 82 percent of the victims while 90 percent
are listed as being of employment age.
</P>
<P>
Out of the total, 26 were foreigners from Thailand and Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's HIV cases are related to drug addiction
and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to raise awareness about AIDS, more than 33,000
officials from national AIDS prevention centers took part in
various AIDS prevention programs in 1996, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Educational programs also targeted 11,000 female prostitutes
and 8,742 drug-addicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Part-time Forces to Be Redesigned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Part-time forces of South
African army will be redesigned by April 1 due to budget cuts in
recent years, the South African National Defense Force (SANDF)
said in an internal communication bulletin today.
</P>
<P>
Superfluous personnel must be transferred to South African
army headquarters and defense headquarters, where a need for
personnel exists, the bulletin said.
</P>
<P>
Part-time staff serving in affected headquarters, regiments
and battalions should be transferred in terms of a personnel plan
to be compiled by officers commanding and the staff concerned,
it added.
</P>
<P>
Civilians currently serving in the headquarters, regiments
and battalions affected by this redesign must be re-allocated to
appropriate posts.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin said staff who were area-bound and could
therefore not be transferred, could apply for voluntary severance
packages.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils last month said up to
20 percent of all SANDF members could receive retrenchment
packages, most of them from the support services.
</P>
<P>
A 9.4 percent cut in the budgetary allocation to defense this
year was announced by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
