<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 46 Killed by Typhoid Fever in Tajikistan Since January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Typhoid fever has killed at least
46 people and infected 5,000 others since its outbreak in
Tajikistan in January, according to a press release issued here
today by the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
The document warned that the epidemic might spread if urgent
measures were not taken to stop it. The total number of cases
could reach 50,000 to 60,000 and the mortality rate might rise to
10 percent without appropriate antibiotic treatment, it said.
</P>
<P>
But with timely and proper treatment, the rate might be reduced
to less than one percent, the document said.
</P>
<P>
A study carried out by WHO attributed the cause of the disease
to contaminated water in the country, saying that the water in the
capital city of Dushanbe had not been treated for at least three
months.
</P>
<P>
Poor sanitary facilities and hygiene in the country helped
transmit the disease and resulted in its rampant spread, the study
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The Tajikistan government has asked for immediate support from
WHO, which has purchased laboratory facilities and received funds
from Denmark and Sweden to purchase medicine.
</P>
<P>
Japan has announced that it would donate one million
U.S. dollars to help control the serious epidemic in Tajikistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
