<HEADLINE> Kenya Airways to Expand Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Kenya Airways (KA) is expected
to launch a new regular six-flight schedule a week between
Nairobi and Amsterdam and acquire at least three new Boeing
B737-300 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily Nation today quoted KA's Managing
Director Brian Davies as saying in London on Thursday that the
six flights a week service will begin on April 1.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official pointed out that the new schedule is a
joint venture with the KA and Dutch Airlines sharing evenly.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the KA's planes would move from Heathrow's
Terminal 3 in London to Terminal 4 which is friendly to
passengers and the KA would be the only African airlines to have
a presence at Terminal 4.
</P>
<P>
Davies also announced plans to develop Nairobi as an efficient
regional hub in the east African region in the next few years,
which will be used to provide services to many points in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Many facilities and services are being upgraded and a new
transfer lounge is to be constructed at Jomo Kenyatta
International Airport here in Nairobi, he added.
</P>
<P>
Following its privatization, the Kenya Airways is being shared
by the Dutch Airlines (26 percent), the Kenyan government (23
percent), International Emerging Market Funds (14 percent), Kenya
Public and Institutions (34 percent) and airline staff (3
percent).
</P>
<P>
He said that 113,000 Kenyans have bought shares of the
airlines, the largest share-holding spread in the east African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
