<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Team Faces Tough Situation in Fed Cup Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion the United
States will have to beat Japan in a playoff this summer to remain
its winning hope alive in the Fed Cup women's team event.
</P>
<P>
A weak U.S. team was beaten by the Netherlands in the opening
round early this month and will be relegated to Group II unless it
defeats Japan in the home-advantaged playoff round July 12-13.
</P>
<P>
The first-round losers Spain and Germany will also face a fight
to stay in Group 1. Spain will travel to Australia, while Germany
will host Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The results of the draw, held in Luxembourg, were announced
Friday by the International Tennis Federation.
</P>
<P>
Against the Netherlands, the U.S. team was weakened by the
absence of Monica Seles and Lindsay Davenport. Seles had a broken
finger and Davenport was left off the team after a dispute with
captain Martina Navratilova.
</P>
<P>
With Mary Joe Fernandez, Chanda Rubin and Gigi Fernandez making
the team, the Americans were eliminated 3-2 by the Netherlands in
Haarlem.
</P>
<P>
Spain, four-time Fed Cup champion and last year's runner-up,
was humiliated 5-0 by Belgium in the first round.
</P>
<P>
Germany was without injured Steffi Graf and Anke Huber when it
lost 3-2 in Manheim to the Czech Republic. The Germans must now
overcome a Crotian team led by Iva Majoli.
</P>
<P>
The other play-off tie sees Switzerland, led by 16-year-old
sensation Martina Hingis, hosting Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Hingis returned to Kosice, the city of her birth, to lead the
Swiss to victory over Slovakia in a Group II match and now can
take her team into Group 1 with a win over Argentina.
</P>
<P>
In the Group I semifinals the same weekend, the Czech Republic
will host the Netherlands while France will play Belgium in
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
