<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Denounces Shoot-out at Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon denounced today the
killing of seven Israeli schoolgirls by a Jordanian soldier
Thursday, but linked it with the April 1996 massacre of its
civilians by the Israeli forces in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in the capital of Beirut, President Elias
Hrawi said, "We are with the humanitarianism and I condemn what
occurred with the Israeli schoolgirls...but we have the right to
ask whether the world had condemned what Israel did at Qana and
the bloodshed of children and women."
</P>
<P>
More than 100 civilians were killed when Israeli artillery
bombarded a U.N. peacekeeping force camp at Qana on April 18,
1996, making it the bloodiest day in a 17-day Israeli blitz in
the country.
</P>
<P>
A Jordanian soldier opened fire on Thursday morning at an
Israeli bus carrying Israeli schoolgirls who were on a field trip
along the Jordan river, leaving seven of them killed and six
others wounded in the border shooting spree.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering marking the 50th anniversary of the
founding of the Doctor's Syndicate in Lebanon, the Lebanese
president reiterated his country's adherence to a just and
comprehensive peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi noted that his country sent delegates to the Madrid
peace conference in October, 1991, for "solidarity with our Arab
brothers in their causes, not (only) for seeking an
implementation of U.N. Security Council Resolution 425."
</P>
<P>
The resolution calls for an unconditional withdrawal of Israeli
forces from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He said that the occupation of other's lands and violation of
other's sovereignty are "moves against the humanitarianism."
</P>
<P>
Israel has set up the so-called 10,000-square kilometer
"security zone" in south Lebanon in 1985. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
