<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Cotton Price Hike Curbs Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A major hike in local cotton prices
has seriously diminished the appeal of Egypt's textile export in
the fiscal year 1995-96, said the Egyptian Shura (Consultative)
Council in a report wired out today.
</P>
<P>
The textile export, which amounts to about a quarter
of the country's total sales abroad, slumped to 2.245 billion
Egyptian pounds (660 million U.S. dollars) last year from 3
billion pounds (882 million dollars) in 1994-95, said the report
quoted by the Egyptian news agency MENA.
</P>
<P>
The report said industry can do a lot better when given the
availability of high-quality Egyptian cotton, the low-cost and
skilled labor.
</P>
<P>
However, the cotton price hike of 75 percent in the recent
couple of years has eroded the competitiveness of local textile
products on foreign markets, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that the drop in the overall export volume was
curtailed by the increase in exports of knitwears and
ready-to-wear clothes.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry, which is among Egypt's largest foreign
currency earners and one of the huge job-providers, is vital
for the country's industrial and economic structure, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
But high cotton prices have greatly cramped the operations of
the public and private spinning factories alike in the past few
years.
</P>
<P>
Some of the factories are on the verge of bankruptcy while the
total losses sustained by those ailing ones reach 500 million
pounds (about 147 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
