<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Economy Expected To Takes Off On Transportation Wings (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- In spite of the many years spent
cultivating, farmers in an old revolutionary base in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region chopped down their fruit trees
without a minute's hesitation when they learned that the
government intends to build a railway across their orchards.
</P>
<P>
Building roadways to increase wealth has become a common goal
of the people of Guangxi, which has abundant natural resources and
a number of ports on its coastline.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the people of Guangxi donated more than 20 million
yuan (about 2.4 million US dollars) for construction of Qinzhou
Port. One of those affected by the construction was Liang Jinhua,
who lost his farm and had to go look for work at a petroleum
wharf.
</P>
<P>
"Although the port has destroyed our farmland," Liang said, "we
feel certain that we will benefit from the port after it is
completed."
</P>
<P>
From 1991 to 1995, Guangxi's state-owned enterprises spent 73.3
billion yuan on infrastructure and basic industries, including the
Nanning-Wuzhou and Pingguo-Baise highways, the Qinzhou-Beihai
railway, and five ports for 10,000 dwt ships.
</P>
<P>
The massive highway construction project has brought Guangxi
closer to its neighbors. In 1996, the region signed as many as
1,800 economic and technological cooperation agreements that
attracted 1.25 billion yuan from other parts of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
