<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Economy Expected to Take Off on Transportation Wings (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When the Nanning-Kunming railway is completed, ports on the
region's southern coast will be the most convenient access for
southwest China's provinces or regions to the sea.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, we seldom cared about other provinces and
regions," said Yang Yexing, an official at Fangcheng Port, but
"Now we are greatly concerned about any news from other provinces
or regions in the Southwest because our port provides services for
them."
</P>
<P>
Government policy makers have considered transportation as part
of a strategy of speeding up the local economy. This year, the
region's investment in fixed assets will reach 56.8 billion yuan,
primarily for transportation, energy and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Kejie, chairman of the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Regional
Government, is giving priority to developing transportation, and
has come up with an ambitious plan where the combined capacities
of Fangcheng, Qinzhou and Beihai ports will have risen to 25
million tons annually by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Construction of highways has helped the economy of Beihai,
Fangcheng, and Qinzhou ports to take off. Their GNP has maintained
a growth rate of 20 percent or more for several years. Not
surprisingly, the travel time between the regional capital of
Nanning and Qinzhou has gone down from an entire day spent on a
bumpy road to three hours by highway.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
