<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volleyballers Fined, Banned in China's National League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Two players of Beijing have been
fined and banned for the rest of the season on Friday following
their assaults on the referee at a Chinese first-division
volleyball league match last weekend.
</P>
<P>
Ou Nan and Xu Zhihe was each fined 2,000 yuan (241
U.S. dollars), the Chinese Volleyball Association (CVA) said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Ou, apparently angry at the referee's decision on the last
point, abused verbally and kicked the referee after Beijing lost
its away game 3-2 against Hubei on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Xu followed by picking up a courtside stool and trying to hurl
toward the referee, but he was stopped by other officials at the
site.
</P>
<P>
The club was also warned and fined 3,000 yuan (361 dollars) as
its captain Li Mu refused to sign on the results sheet and head
coach Yu Huanzan failed to take prompt action to stop his players
in the incident.
</P>
<P>
The organising committee of Hubei was also penalized by a 5,000
yuan (602 dollars) fine because the local fans threw projectiles
into the court after the players' attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
