<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore to Host Int'l Conference on Confucianism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Singapore is to host an
international conference on Confucianism and World Civilizations
in June with more than 200 scholars from around the world expected
to attend, organizers said here today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, organized by the Center for Research in Chinese
Studies of the Department of Chinese Studies, National University
of Singapore (NUS), in conjunction with the International
Confucian Association, aims to promote the study of Confucianism,
Dr. Tan Eng-Chaw said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Tan, head of the NUS Department of Chinese Studies and
Director of the Center, said that the focus of discussion at the
conference would be on the past, present, and future development
of Confucianism and its interaction with world civilizations.
</P>
<P>
"With the economic success of the East Asian countries and the
Asian Four Little Dragons, Confucian studies have attracted
worldwide attention. Besides the pragmatic aspects and moral
values of Confucianism, the interaction between Confucianism and
other civilizations have become an important topic of discussion,"
he noted.
</P>
<P>
Professor Zhu Bokun of Beijing University, Professor Tu Wei
Ming of Harvard University, and Professor Wm. Theodore de Bary of
Columbia University are among the scholars expected to attend the
conference, Dr Tan said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
