<HEADLINE> '97 Urumqi Economic, Trade Talks to Open in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The '97 Urumqi Economic and Trade
Talks is scheduled to run from September 1-8 this year in the city
of Urumqi, capital of Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Regional government Abul'ahat Abdurixit made
the announcement to a group of Chinese and foreign journalists as
well as officials from 15 foreign embassies at today's news
conference held at the Xinjiang Office in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Present at the briefing were Vice-Chairman of the National
People's Congress National Committee Temur Dawamad, State
Councilor Ismail Amat, Secretary of the Regional Committee of the
Communist Party of China Wang Lequan, Guo Dongpo, president of the
China Council for Promoting International Trade.
</P>
<P>
Five such talks have been held in the past and have received a
total of over 11,000 business people from 65 foreign countries and
regions, with the trading volume totaling 5.6 billion US dollars,
according to the chairman.
</P>
<P>
The regional leader said that the Urumqi fair has become a
major international trade event in west China and an important
bridge for the country's efforts to open up its western part to
the rest of the world, especially to the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is a resource-rich and generally uncultivated land, he
said, noting that the autonomous region now has over 3.2 million
ha. of farmland and over 6.66 million ha. of wasteland.
</P>
<P>
Reserves of 138 mineral resources, such as oil, gas and coal,
have been verified in Xinjiang, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Xinjiang has made tremendous achievements and
progress in economic and social fields. In 1996, the region
generated 79.7 billion yuan in gross domestic product (the value
of goods and services produced), 7.8 million tons of grain,
950,000 tons of cotton, 14.35 million tons of crude oil and 13.3
billion kwh of electricity.
</P>
<P>
The local infrastructure and investment have been greatly
improved, he said. According to official figures, the state
investment in local infrastructural sectors such as railroads and
the power industry has increased by 25 percent annually over the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said that Xinjiang, where people are enjoying
political stability, national unity, economic development, social
progress and a happy life, has provided a sound social environment
for domestic and foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
