<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority of China's Workers Benefit From Reforms, Opening Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A majority of Chinese workers say
that the quality of life has improved over the past decade and
that they hope the country's stability and fast economic growth
will continue.
</P>
<P>
These attitudes were revealed by a survey done jointly by the
State Statistics Bureau, the People's Bank of China, the All-China
Federation of Trade Unions, and the ministries of civil affairs,
public health, and labor from December of last year to January.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered 30,000 urban households across China, 80.6
percent of the respondents said that the quality of life was
better than ten years ago and 15.5 percent of them said that they
had seen "great improvement" in their lives.
</P>
<P>
Some 62.7 percent of the respondents said that the quality of
life was clearly better than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
In answer to questions about major concerns, workers said that
social stability and national economic growth were the major ones,
followed by social security and corruption.
</P>
<P>
Chinese workers are also concerned about medical care reforms,
inflation, housing reforms, welfare reforms, pensions, and wage
adjustments. Then come children's education and the growing
disparity between incomes.
</P>
<P>
The survey noted an indifference to the lives of movie stars
and celebrities. Only one out of 200 questioned showed a great
deal of interest in the lives or careers of stars and celebs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
