<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Statistics Shows Continuing Economic Slide in Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The economic slide started in
the second half of 1996 continued unchecked in the first two
months this year, said the Mongolian State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The expenditures in the first two months totalled 29 billion
tugriks (one U.S. dollar for 782.18 tugriks) and budgetary
revenues amounted to 28.8 billion tugriks, registering a deficit
of 200 million tugriks, according to the statistics released by
the bureau today.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that the country's import-export volume declined
to 80.1 million U.S. dollars in the first two months, accounting
for 66.6 percent of that in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The prices of commodities and service increased 3.2 percent in
February from the previous month and 5.6 percent over December
last year.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output totalled 30.5 billion tugriks in the
first two months this year, down 600 million tugriks or 1.8
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia lost 145,300 heads of grown animals by March 1,
129,200 more than the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The statistics bureau said the number of registered jobless
people hit 575,000, posting a slight increase of 2,133 from the
end of last year.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,005 cases of crime were reported in the first two
months this year, up 21 percent over the same period last
year. Two hundred and sixteen people were killed and 820 injured
in various crimes, which caused 17.1 billion tugriks in economic
losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
