<HEADLINE> Guangnan Supermarket Launches Expansion Campaign in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Guangnan (KK) Supermarket, a
subsidiary of Chinese-funded food distributor Guangnan (Holdings),
 is planning an expansion campaign to challenge Hong Kong's two
dominant supermarket chains.
</P>
<P>
The company plans to invest some 20 million HK dollars (2.6
million US dollars) to open as many as 10 new KK supermarkets this
year, while boosting business at its existing 35 stores by
carrying a wider variety than its competitors.
</P>
<P>
KK General Manager Yeung Wing-tung said the investment will be
financed primarily from internal resources with the balance coming
from bank loans.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the new supermarkets will be built around new
towns and will offer customers larger fresh-food counters.
</P>
<P>
"We will offer more choices, more fresh food," he promised,
saying his company will have advanced knowledge about new types of
fresh food being developed in the Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
For years Hong Kong's supermarket business has been dominated
by Park N' Shop and Wellcome, each having around 200 stores across
the territory.
</P>
<P>
Since KK's sister company in the Chinese mainland is also
expanding very fast, "our combined strength in the next five years
hopefully may surpass our competitors in Hong Kong," said Yeung.
</P>
</TEXT>
