<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> C-130 Plane Crashes with 80 People on Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian plane with 80
people on board crashed in Iran's northeastern province of
Khorasan last night, an official report said here today.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the C-130 plane,
belonging to Iran's armed services, crashed en route from Dezful
to Mashhad 18:00 local time (14:30 GMT) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 80 passengers and crew members were believed to be killed,
although the wreckage has not been found yet so far.
</P>
<P>
Governor Vakilipour of Mashhad said Friday that an
team has been dispatched to the possible crash site to conduct
initial investigations and organize rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
Vakilipour said the team has failed to find the wreckage and
given no report on the passengers' fate so far .
</P>
<P>
The plane lost contact with the control tower at Mashhad
airport about one hour after take-off from Dezful. The state-run
Tehran Radio reported that the C-130 plane disappeared over the
city of Neyshabur and probably crashed in the area about 700
kilometers northeast of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the pilot first reported problems with
the engines and dispatched emergency signal "SOS" before the
communication was cut off.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Iranian aviation authorities have already sent
a special plane to find out the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
Iran was believed to have some 20 C-130 planes, which suffered
a lack of spare parts and services because of U.S. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
