<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Nationwide War Against Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today ordered Interior Secretary Robert Barbers to mount a
nationwide war against organized crimes, including kidnapping,
bank robbery, drug trafficking and other illegal activities in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement, the presidential palace said that Ramos,
in his hand-written instruction, ordered Barbers to intensify
anti-kidnap and anti-crime drive by utilizing the community,
law-enforcement agencies, prosecutors, courts and correctional
institutions.
</P>
<P>
It said that the president also ordered the country's police
chief, defense secretary, justice secretary and other senior
officials to provide Barbers all the assistance and support he
needs in waging a war against crimes.
</P>
<P>
According to the presidential palace, Ramos' order is the
government's reaction to a report by the U.S. Fortune magazine
which labeled the Philippines as "the kidnapping capital of Asia."
</P>
<P>
The magazine said in a recent issue that 241 people were
kidnapped for ransom in the Philippines in 1996, nearly double the
official figure for the previous year.
</P>
<P>
It said that kidnapping statistics are "greatly under-stated"
in the country because many victims are too frightened to complain
to the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
