<HEADLINE> Presidential Rule Extended in Uttar Pradesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The on-going session of the
lower house of parliament today approved the United Front
government's resolution, again extending presidential rule in
Uttar Pradesh for another six months beyond April 17.
</P>
<P>
The resolution placed before the house by Union Home Minister
Indrajit Gupta on Thursday was put to vote by Speaker P.A. Sangma
without discussion and was carried by a voice of vote.
</P>
<P>
This is the third extension of presidential rule in Uttar
Pradesh due to its uncertainties and law and order situation in
that state.
</P>
<P>
Since last year there has been two successive extensions of
presidential rule in the state.
</P>
<P>
Last November, assembly elections were held in the state but no
single political party secured required seats to form a
government. As a result, the union government was forced to extend
presidential rule in that state.
</P>
<P>
Since then various political forces have maneuvered again to
muster enough support to form a government, but they failed.
</P>
<P>
The law and order situation has been deteriorating day by day
in the state.
</P>
<P>
The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the biggest opposition in
parliament, walked out of the house protesting against the
government's resolution. Before walking out, BJP deputy leader
Jaswant Singh said that his party had reservations on the
extension of presidential rule and had to register its protest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
