<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official: Gaza Conference Turning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official said
today President Yasser Arafat's call for an international
conference to examine the recent Israeli moves is a turning point
in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Finance Minister Mohammed Zuhdi Nashashibi told
the Cairo-based Voice of Arab radio that Saturday's gathering in
Gaza would "lead to a fresh development in the peace-making
process, though it raises the concern of the Israelis."
</P>
<P>
Humiliated and frustrated by the recent Israeli plans for new
settlement and limited Israeli redeployment, Arafat called for
international intervention Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Arab rage has flared since Israel decided to build 6,500
Jewish homes and close four Palestinian offices in East Jerusalem,
as well as to withdraw its troops from 9 percent of the West Bank
instead of 30 percent as demanded by the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Nashashibi expected that the Gaza gathering would help make
Israel reconsider its positions and respect the basis upon which
the peace process was started.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Israeli government to drop the settlement scheme
in Jabal Abu Ghneim, also known as Har Homa, as it might blast
the whole Mideast peace march.
</P>
<P>
"This could be the straw that breaks the camel's back," he
said, adding that it could be a sheer disaster if the Israelis
ignore the will of the Palestinian people, other Arabs and the
peace-loving forces.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the United States to restore its basic role as
the honest sponsor of the peace process. The U.S., also Israel's
closest ally, vetoed last week a U.N. Security Council resolution
condemning Israel's settlement policy, but later announced to send
an envoy to the Gaza conference apparently in a bid to ease the
Arab anger.
</P>
<P>
Israel, however, refused to attend the meeting on grounds that
such a gathering violated the autonomy agreements stipulating that
disputes between Israel and Palestine must be resolved in a way
agreed by both sides.
</P>
<P>
It has ruled out the possibility of retracting from its early
decisions simply out of pressure or "the threat of violence.'
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Palestinian Council, in a statement released
Thursday, called for suspending negotiations with Israel which it
accused of leading the peace march to "a real crisis."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have reportedly so far refused to coordinate
with Israel on the transfer of authority slated for a pullback,
putting the redeployment on hold. Seven Palestinian cabinet
ministers have even threatened to resign to show their outrage
over "Israel's real intention for peace."
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai have made it clear that Israel would
not back down from its recent decisions that fueled the Arab
rage.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Egypt's Assistant Foreign Minister
for Arab Affairs Badr Hamam will leave here today for Gaza to join
envoys from the U.S., Russia, the European Union, Japan, Norway
and Jordan at the international conference aimed to save the peace
process from collapse.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a key mediator in the peace process, has been the
strongest advocate of the Palestinian cause. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
