<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Sign Border Disarmament Agreement with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China will sign a border
disarmament agreement with Russia and three central Asian
countries during President Jiang Zemin's state visit to Russia in
coming April.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng revealed the news here today when he met
reporters covering the annual session of the National People's
Congress, which closed today.
</P>
<P>
The agreement on the reduction of military forces in the border
area will be signed by the heads of states of China, Russia,
Kazakhstan, Kyrghyzstan and Tajikistan, said Li.
</P>
<P>
"With the signing of this agreement," the premier pointed out,
"the border that we share with the four countries will be a border
for cooperation and good neighborliness."
</P>
<P>
He added the leaders of China and Russia will exchange views on
the international situation and issue an important political
document during Jiang's visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
He also made a brief explanation on the strategic partnership
for cooperation, established between China and Russia last April,
that is geared toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning the fact that China and Russia share a border of
over 7000 km, he noted China hopes that the two countries will
have a friendly relationship.
</P>
<P>
The premier added that the two economies are "highly
complementary," and that China wishes to develop Sino-Russian
cooperation in economic, trade and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Both China and Russia are important countries, Li noted, and
both countries hope to play their roles in facilitating regional
and world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
"So, such a strategic partnership for cooperation is not
directed at any third country," the premier said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
