<HEADLINE> 56 Million Nigerians Registered for Local </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Some 55.7 million Nigerians among
its total population of nearly 100 million have been registered
as voters for Saturday's local government election on party
basis, the National Electoral Commission announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commission chairman Sumner Dagogo-Jack said in Nigeria's
capital of Abuja the voters' registration took place from
February 10 to 19.
</P>
<P>
The figure is five million less than the 60.6 million
suggested by the commission in its preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
It is also five million more than the number of eligible
voters (18 years and above) as estimated by the National
Population Commission, the chairman said.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's election is a major step in the transition to civil
rule program of the Nigerian military government headed by
General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
Other major events under the transition program set for 1997
include the election of state assembly and governors. But as the
local election had been delayed for three months, they are likely
to be postponed too.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
