<HEADLINE> Conditions Nearly Ripe for Resolving Hwang Incident: Li Peng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said at a
press meeting here this afternoon that the conditions are almost
ripe for resolving the Hwang Jang-yop incident.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the incident occurred in China, and in accordance
with the universally-recognized conventions of the international
law, China, as a sovereign state, has the full right of
jurisdiction over the incident.
</P>
<P>
"For the same reason, China does not recognize the right of
diplomatic asylum by foreign embassies and consulates in its
territory," Li Peng said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side is very prudent in handling this incident,
mainly proceeding from the question of maintaining peace and
stability on the Korean Peninsular, according to the premier.
</P>
<P>
In the entire course of handling this case, Li said, "We
should, of course, take into account the stances of all the
parties concerned, and resolve the issue properly as soon as
possible in accordance with the relevant international laws.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the conditions are almost ripe for resolving
this incident," Premier Li told reporters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
