<HEADLINE> At Least 13 Killed in Southern Egypt Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Unidentified gunmen shot dead at
least 13 civilians and wounded seven others in two separate
shooting attacks Thursday night in southern Egypt, the Egyptian
news agency MENA reported today.
</P>
<P>
An Interior Ministry source was quoted as saying that in the
first shooting, which took place at 8 p.m.(18:00 GMT), masked
gunmen gun down 12 Egyptian men walking on a dirt road near Naga
Hamadi, a mostly Coptic Christian village 460 kilometers south of
the Egyptian capital.
</P>
<P>
The unnamed source said eight of the victims were Coptic
Christians. The assailants, who were suspected Muslim militants,
fled the scene after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
The second attack occurred in the same area before midnight
when unidentified attackers fired at a Cairo-bound train from the
tourist city of Luxor, killing a 40-year-old housewife and
injuring six others.
</P>
<P>
The train came under fire when it was passing by the Abu Tesht
railway station near Naga Hamadi.
</P>
<P>
Local security forces quickly rushed to the scene and launched
an intensive manhunt in the nearby villages for the assailants.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's attacks were among the worst ones on Christians
since 1992 when Muslim militants killed 12 Christian villagers in
Assiut of southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
It came exactly a month after the Egyptian government vowed to
strike hard at extremist activities in the event of the February
13 church attack. Nine Copts were killed and six others injured
when gunmen opened fire at a Coptic church in Minya, 240
kilometers south of Cairo in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The militants have waged a violent campaign attempting to
establish a strict Islamic state in Egypt since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,070 people have been killed in the clashes, mostly
civilians and police. Extremist attacks have also targeted Copts,
whom they view as apostates.
</P>
<P>
In the predominantly Muslim country, Copts make up about 10
percent of Egypt's 60 million population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
