<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- All the big cities of Albania, including Tirana, are being
tormented by chaos. In a state where no one can control the
situation, President Berisha and the new government of "national
reconciliation" have launched an appeal for military intervention
by Europe -- without success up to now.
</P>
<P>
-- Burundi Thursday claimed that it foiled a coup attempt by
"Tutsi extremists." Burundian security forces arrested six
people, including two former army officers, who were close to
former President Jean-Baptiste Bagaza, after seven people were
killed on Wednesday in an explosion of landmines in the capital
Bujumbura.
</P>
<P>
-- The International Federation of Red Cross announced on
Thursday that it is dispatching 10 million U.S. dollars worth of
food and medicines to Iraq. It said that 50,000 Iraqi children
are facing severe mal-nutrition and blamed the United Nations for
being too slow in applying its "Oil for Food" program with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Albania has been plunged into full chaos after 600 prisoners
escaped from prison in Tirana and Shkodra, the biggest city in
northern Albania. Having failed to stop the turmoil from turning
into a civil war, the Albanian government and the opposition have
called for an armed intervention by Europe.
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Alain Juppe Thursday launched a
campaign baptized "Act for Protection of Maltreated Children" to
mobilize public opinion on a national level against abuse of
children. France registered 65,000 cases of abuse or maltreatment
of children in 1995.
</P>
<P>
-- Violent fightings went on Thursday near the eastern Zairean
city of Kisangani, during which the Zairean army tried to loosen
the stranglehold by the rebel troops of Laurent-Desire Kabila. In
three days of fighting, the government troops could not repel the
rebels but by five kilometers. The rebels are only 40 to 60
kilometers from Kisangani. 
</P>
</TEXT>
