<HEADLINE> Turkish Aircraft Industry to Get U.S. Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is working on a proposal
to transfer the U.S. shares in the F-16 producer Turkish
Aerospace Industries (TAI) to Koc Holding, the largest industrial
company in the country.
</P>
<P>
The plan drawn by the Office of the General Staff and the
Undersecretariat for the Defense Industry will be discussed at
the upcoming TAI executive board meeting, the local newspaper Daily
News quoted today senior defense sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier agreement, 40 percent of the
U.S. shares in the TAI should be transferred to Turkey when
the F-16 production program ends.
</P>
<P>
The Koc Holding will be given priority in obtaining the
U.S. shares, due to its background with the defense
industry, the sources said, adding the Sabanci Holding, the
second largest company in Turkey, would be the next on the list.
</P>
<P>
The TAI has been producing F-16 fighters and other types of
aircraft since 1987 under a foreign license. To date, the company
has produced nearly 160 F-16 jets for Turkey and 46 other aircraft
for the Egyptian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
The same sources said that due to technical insufficiency,
U.S. firms, Lockheed and General Electrics, still hold nearly
half of the total TAI shares. The TAI was originally set up to
develop Turkey's own aircraft industry.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. firms' reaction to the proposal remains unknown so
far, the defense sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
