<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish President Sides with Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel has stressed that the military was not interested in
running the country but forced to put pressure on the Islamist
coalition government to battle fundamentalists.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the local newspaper Daily News,
Demirel said the military led by Chief of General Staff
Ismail Hakki Karadayi was not concerned with the strength of
Islam in Turkey but would not like to see attempts to use Islam for
political purpose.
</P>
<P>
The interview came off the press today.
</P>
<P>
Over the past weeks, tension was felt between the pro-Islam
government and the military, which has a tradition of defending
secularism in light of increasing fundamentalist activities in the
secular republic.
</P>
<P>
Military commanders put forward a 22-point communique at the
February 28 military-dominated National Security Council (NSC)
recommending the coalition government take quick and effective
measures against the growth of fundamentalist influence.
</P>
<P>
Islamist Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan, also leader of the
Welfare Party, has reluctantly signed the communique in order to
avoid collapse of his coalition with Tansu Ciller's True Path
Party.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing Turkey was a modern republic, Demirel said:"Its
People are Muslims but the state has no religion. If some people
object to this they have to know there is no alternative and the
country will move ahead on this course."
</P>
<P>
He said the problems in the past weeks showed that the
military was disturbed because these limitations had been
violated.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the only remedy to break the
bottlenecks in the country's political life was elections, adding
the country should wait until it gets a parliament determined to
defend democracy.
</P>
<P>
After Erbakan came to power last summer as the republic's first
ever pro-Islam prime minister, the fundamentalist activities made a
remarkable growth in the country, alarming the military loyal to
the secular system established by the founder of modern Turkey,
Kemel Ataturk.
</P>
<P>
The Welfare Party recently proposed that women civil servants
should wear Islamic-style scarf in government offices and a
mosque be built in one of the main commercial squares in
Istanbul, the country's largest city, triggering strong criticism
from the secular forces backed by the military.
</P>
<P>
In the confrontation, President Demirel sided with the
military, calling for pressure on Erbakan to compromise.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the coalition cabinet formally agreed to implement
the NSC recommendations for curbing the growth of fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Thursday's cabinet meeting, Erbakan unexpectedly told
the press that in line with the Constitution, the NSC
recommendations would be given the first place on the agenda. His
statement was widely seen here as a sharp contrast with his
previous attitude.
</P>
<P>
Before the signing of the NSC document, he vowed that his
government was constitutionally responsible for the parliament,
implying that he would not be subject to pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
