<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Gore Will be Accorded Friendly Reception:" Chinese Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice-President Al Gore will
be accorded a friendly reception in China, Chinese Premier Li Peng
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting with domestic and foreign reporters
covering the National People's Congress and answering a question
concerning the coming visit to China by US Vice-President Al Gore,
Premier Li Peng said, "At my invitation, Vice-President Al Gore
will soon visit China. This visit will be an important event in
relations between China and the United States."
</P>
<P>
"One of the important tasks for Vice-President Al Gore during
his visit is to prepare for a meeting between the top leaders of
China and US, which will take place later this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
"While Vice-President Al Gore is in China, we will also
co-chair a forum to discuss environmental protection and
development issues. And we will also have an exchange of views on
other issues of mutual interest," the Chinese Premier said.
</P>
<P>
"Vice-President Al Gore will be accorded a friendly reception
in China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China is the biggest developing country and the United States
is the most developed country in the world. So our two countries
exercise major influences in the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Owing to differences in ideology because of our different
social systems, we have some disagreements. But we have to reduce
confrontation and develop cooperation in order to develop our
relations on a normal track," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Maintaining a healthy and stable development of Sino-US
relations will be in the interest of world peace and stability,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"In handling international relations, the Chinese government
always maintains that all countries regardless of their size
should be all treated as equals. And what China opposes most is
interference in other countries' internal affairs. And in this
matter China has been a victim," he added.
</P>
<P>
Since China itself is strongly opposed to interference in
internal affairs from other countries, naturally, China will be
the last country to interfere in or influence the internal affairs
of other countries in any form, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
