<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Makes No Deal With Imelda on Marcos' Burial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Press Secretary Hector
Villanueva reiterated here today that President Fidel Ramos had
made no written commitment to former first lady Imelda Marcos on
the burial of the remains of her late husband at the Manila
Heroes' Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva made the remarks after the Presidential Palace
released a copy of the joint statement issued by the then
president-elect and Mrs. Marcos following their meeting at the
residence of House Speaker Jose de Venecia in June in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Imelda said Ramos gave her a handwritten promise during the
meeting to allow the body of the late president Ferdinand Marcos
to be buried at the heroes' cemetery. The Marcoses threatened to
show the promise to the public after Ramos denied issuing such an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"President-elect Fidel Ramos met tonight with former First Lady
Imelda Romualdez-Marcos and both agreed to contribute efforts to
achieve political stability and economic prosperity for the
country," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement co-signed by Ramos and Imelda did not say that
Ramos had made any handwritten promise to bury Marcos as a hero.
</P>
<P>
The Marcoses had stepped up pressure on the government to allow
the burial of Marcos' remains after the power supply to his crypt
was cut off March 3 due to the family's failure to pay power
bills.
</P>
<P>
The remains of Marcos were returned to his hometown in the
northern Philippines from Hawaii, the United States in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
