<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remains of Earliest Chinese Observatory Found in Henan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The remains of an observatory
dating back 4,000 years have been found in central China's Henan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts say that the Huoxing Tai (Mars Observatory),
located some 1.5 km to the southwest of Shangqiu county, is the
earliest ever found in China.
</P>
<P>
The observatory has a temple on top. A main hall, side
chambers, and bell and drum towers can still be discerned in the
temple. An observatory tower was built at the back of the main
hall, according to records, which was destroyed during wartime.
</P>
<P>
According to historical documents, archaeological finds, and
astronomical records, Huoxing Tai was used during the reign of
Emperor Yao, who appointed Que Bo as the official in charge of the
observatory. The Que Bo Temple bore the official's name.
</P>
<P>
The village at the foot of the observatory is named "Huoxing", a
name that has not changed for thousands of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
