<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng on China's Entry into WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng said here
today that China has enough patience to wait for its entry into
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Answering questions during a meeting with Chinese and foreign
reporters covering the Fifth Session of the Eighth National
People's Congress, which closed here today, Li said that as a
major trading nation in the world, China is eager to join the WTO,
and has made great efforts in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"We have reduced the average import tariff rate to 23 percent
from 35 percent and made the commitment to further cut the rate to
15 percent by the end of the century, about the average level for
developing countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that China welcomes recent progress in talks on Chinese
accession to the WTO, the premier said it is abnormal that China
has been unable to join the WTO for a long period of time.
</P>
<P>
"Granted that economic interests have played a part in this,
there is no denying that this has also been due to political
factors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I can reiterate on behalf of the Chinese government that,
after joining the WTO, China will fulfill its obligations while
enjoying rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that it is known to all that China is still a
developing country and that it is unacceptable to apply to China
criteria for developed countries concerning its accession to the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
"China needs the WTO, and the WTO also needs China," he said,
adding that relevant countries should take a sensible attitude
so that the issue will be resolved as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"I can tell you, however, that China has enough patience to
wait," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
