<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reveal Secrets of Lost Ancient Kingdom in Southwest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese idiom "Yelang zi da"
(referring to the conceit of the king of Yelang) is widely used by
Chinese to comment on someone's ridiculous arrogance, but its
origin may not be so well known.
</P>
<P>
About the only thing really known about Yelang is that it was a
kingdom in southwestern China in modern-day Sichuan, Yunnan, and
Guizhou provinces and the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The kingdom prospered during the early Western Han Dynasty (206
BC-24 AD), but vanished mysteriously in the middle of the dynasty,
leaving few records.
</P>
<P>
To uncover the kingdom's secrets, a meeting, attended by more
than 50 scholars from the three provinces and the autonomous
region, was recently held in Guiyang, the capital of Guizhou,
which is believed to be the original place of the ancient kingdom
of Yelang.
</P>
<P>
The research on Yelang is one of major archaeological projects
in the 1996-2000 period in Guizhou. To date, scholars have made a
detailed study of the limited number of historical records and are
now turning to site work.
</P>
<P>
A great number of sites and tomb groups from the Warring States
Period (475-221 BC), the Qin (221-206 BC) and the Han (206 BC-220
AD) dynasties have been found in Guizhou since the 1970s, and the
way has been opened for excavation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
