<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing, a New Municipality with Regional Specialties (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The special features of
Chongqing reflect the central authorities' intention to accelerate
economic development in central and western China.
</P>
<P>
As the largest industrial city in southwestern Sichuan
Province, Chongqing was designated to be a provincial-level
municipality here today, according to a resolution adopted at the
closing meeting of the fifth session of the Eighth National
People's Congress (NPC), the legislature. And it is the first
municipality in China's central and western region.
</P>
<P>
When compared with China's three other municipalities --
Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin -- Chongqing now has many unique
characteristics, which experts say reflect the central
authorities' intention to speed up development in the central and
western China.
</P>
<P>
In terms of economic regions, Chongqing belongs both to the
southwestern region and to the Yangtze River valley. It is also
located within the jurisdictive area of Three Gorges Dam project.
</P>
<P>
As a new municipality with an area of 82,400 sq km, Chongqing
has about the same size of a medium-sized province, or 2.39 times
the combined area of Shanghai, Beijing and Tianjin. With 43
districts and counties under its jurisdiction, it has a population
of 30.2 million, or 83.2 percent of the combined population of the
other three municipalities. These features make Chongqing China's
biggest city and a rare, super-large city in the world.
</P>
<P>
A breakdown shows that 24.40 million of the Chongqing
residents, or 81.37 percent of the total, live in the outskirtan
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the other three municipalities, Chongqing boasts
abundant natural resources. It has 41 rivers each with a drained
area of more than 500 sq km. It has some 40 mineral resources,
such as natural gas, bauxite, salt, strontium and limestone. In
addition, new Chongqing is also rich in tourist resources, such as
the Three Gorges area and other world-famous landscapes.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, in terms of economic strength, Chongqing is
apparently behind the three other municipalities, an indication of
the disparity in economic development between the eastern and
western regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing, a New Municipality with Regional Specialties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Chongqing leads Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin only in term
of agricultural output, whereas it lags behind the other three
cities in term of total industrial output value, fiscal revenue,
retail sales of consumer goods, foreign trade and investment in
fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output value of Shanghai, Beijing and Tianjin is
4.89 times, 1.84 times and 1.73 times respectively that of
Chongqing. And in term of trade export volume, Shanghai, Beijing
and Tianjin lead Chongqing by 14.88, 6.75 and 5.2 times,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The living standards of Chongqing's urban and rural residents
is below the average national level and the per-capita income of
its farmers ranks the 23rd place in the country.
</P>
<P>
Resettlement in the Three Gorges Dam area, which involves new
Chongqing's 18 districts and counties, will inundate 36,700
hectares of land and 1,300 enterprises and mines. Five county
seats will be submerged completely and three new cities partly
under the water. A total of 1.07 million people will be relocated
eventually.
</P>
<P>
New Chongqing has 12 state-level and nine province-level
poverty-stricken counties, with a total of three million locals in
need. Moreover, it also has five autonomous counties of national
minorities with more than 1.7 million people of ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Chongqing became one of the first group of selected
cities to experiment with comprehensive economic reforms and was
granted the status of a Chinese province in the administration of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, it was again designated an open city along the Yangtze
River and was granted the preferential policies that had been set
especially for coastal open cities.
</P>
<P>
As it is upgraded to be a municipality directly under the
central authorities, Chongqing has a legislative power and other
powers of jurisdiction that are not entitled to some special
cities with the status of a province. Chongqing has entered into a
new historical period with both huge opportunities and challenges
and it is expected to exert a far-reaching impact on the economic
development of central and western China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing: Its Past and Present </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Chinese historians claim that the
history of Chongqing, the largest city in southwest China that was
upgraded to be a provincial-level municipality today, epitomizes
the history of Chinese cities in the central and western region.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing rises from an ancient regional military and political
center to a regional economic hub, from a seclusive site of
castles to an open strategic hub linking the east and west, and
from a medium-sized city in eastern Sichuan to a super-large
metropolis with its impact expected to amplify to southwest China
and the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Historian Yu Weichao, director of the Museum of Chinese
History, described the 600 km section of the Yangtze River under
Chongqing's jurisdiction as one of the important places where the
Chinese civilization originates.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, as the birthplace of Bayu Culture, has a recorded
history of more than 3,000 years. It was made the capital of State
Ba in the 11th century B.C., renamed Yuzhou in the year 581 and
changed into Chongqing in the year 1189.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou Yong, an expert on the history of Chongqing,
the municipality became a commercial hub and the largest commodity
distribution center in southwest China during the Ming (1368-1644)
and Qing (1644-1911) dynasties. It was forced into a trading port
in 1891.
</P>
<P>
In 1929, Chongqing was turned into a city. The government of
the Kuomintang government moved to Chongqing after the War of
Resistance against Japanese Aggression broke out in 1937, followed
by the relocation of coastal industries to the interior, and this
was the first large-scale immigration in the city's history. The
migration laid the foundation of Chongqing as an industrial base.
The Kuomintang government officially upgraded it to be a "special
city" in 1939 and, a year later, renamed it the "wartime capital".
</P>
<P>
After the founding of new China in 1949, Chongqing became a
political, economic and cultural center in southwestern China and
a municipality under the direct jurisdiction of the central
government. Under the leadership of Deng Xiaoping, Liu Bocheng and
He Long, Chongqing played a unique role in the complete fulfilment
of the tasks for China's New-Democratic Revolution and the
consolidation and development of its socialist political power.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the central government in 1954 redesignated
Chongqing a city under the jurisdiction of the Sichuan provincial
government and granted it the power to make economic decisions on
its own.
</P>
<P>
A concentration of investment in military-related industries
between 1964 and 1968 led to the second large-scale migration in
Chongqing's history, with more than 200 projects relocated or
launched at a total investment of 4.2 billion yuan. As a result,
Chongqing's industrial sectors became more complete and its
overall economic strength ascended to a new height.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1980s, Chongqing's industrial output was about 20
percent of the total of the three provinces in southwest China and
one third of Sichuan's.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, Chongqing was again granted the power of making
economic plans on its own and the power of a province in economic
administration. It also became the first large city to experiment
with comprehensive economic structural reforms.
</P>
<P>
Over the past ten or more years, Chongqing scored great
achievements in reform, opening up and development and, it
attained the goal of quadrupling its 1980 gross domestic product
by the end of 1995, five years ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The upgrading it to be a municipality at the provincial-level
provides Chongqing with an opportunity to make itself a central
city on the upper reaches of the Yangze river, which is expected
to lead economic development in the country's southwestern region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
