<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lung Transplant Recipient Two Years After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Two years after lung transplant
surgery, Ji Shuchun takes care of himself and does house work in
his hometown of Anyang City, central China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Ji is longest-lived recipient of a lung-transplant in
Asia. Beijing Anzhen Hospital, which performed the operation, held
a special birthday party for him earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Ji told Xinhua that he eats well and has much strength, adding
that he buys vegetables and helps his wife make meals everyday and
often rides a tricycle.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, Ji Shuchun, a farmer, barely able to breathe,
was completely unable to do any physical labor. Doctors at Beijing
Anzhen Hospital after several exams decided that transplant
surgery offered Ji his best hope.
</P>
<P>
After the successful operation, the hospital rescued Ji from
severe tissue-rejection reactions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia, Indonesia Settle Maritime Boundaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Australia and Indonesia signed
an agreement today, settling the outstanding international
maritime boundaries between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer and his Indonesian counterpart Ali Alatas in
Perth.
</P>
<P>
Downer described the treaty, which must now be ratified by the
parliaments of both countries, as fair and equitable, and said,
"our national interests have been well protected and well
promoted."
</P>
<P>
Alatas, who arrived in Perth last night, said, "this treaty is
a landmark in the history of relations between Indonesia and
Australia, and will keep strengthening our already close and
cordial relations."
</P>
<P>
The maritime treaty ended negotiations which began in the
1960s, when the two countries first began discussing maritime
boundary issues.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, which affects fishing rights and seabed mineral
exploration, covers three previously unresolved areas, including
the seabed boundary and the Exclusive Economic Zone boundary, also
known as the water column boundary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
