<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Doctors Call Off Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan Government Medical
 Officers Association (GMOA) has called off the strike it was due
to launch today, according to the GMOA sources here.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the decision to call off the strike
followed a meeting the GMOA had with the Cabinet Sub-Committee
(CSC) appointed by the government to look into the salary
anomalies.
</P>
<P>
The sources stated that they had a meeting with CSC Thursday
and they are satisfied with it.
</P>
<P>
The CSC was appointed by the government following a token
strike launched by doctors in state-run hospitals on February 27.
But the 24 hour strike ended in eight hours following assurances
given by the government that their grievances will be looked
into.
</P>
<P>
However, the GMOA expressed dissatisfaction at the manner in
which the committee was handling their problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
