<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Find Proves Existence of Mesolithic Age in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A great number of tiny blade
tools dating back more than 10,000 years have been found in
northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, suggesting the
existence of Middle Stone Age with microlithic products.
</P>
<P>
Traditionally, the Stone Age is divided into the Palaeolithic,
or Early Stone Age (some two million to 10,000 years ago), which
features chipped stone tools, and the Neolithic, or Late Stone Age
(10,000 to 4,000 years ago), which features polished stone tools.
</P>
<P>
A number of archaeologists have previously suggested that a
Mesolithic, or Middle Stone Age, which features tiny blade tools,
might have existed for a short period of time at the end of the
traditional Early Stone Age, a view that was not widely accepted
because of a lack of relics.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, 1995, and 1996, a Sino-US archaeology team excavated a
Paleolithic site at Gezi Shan (Dove Mountain) in Jiangding
township, Qingtongxia city, in Ningxia and found a great number of
stone tools in a five-sq-km area.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tools were microlithic tools such as cores, small
blades, scrapers, and pointed implements made from different
colors of chert, a flintlike stone. They were made with a method
referred to as "indirect chipping", where something was placed in
between the object striking and the object doing the chipping,
which is regarded as a step up in the evolution of the use of
stone tools.
</P>
<P>
The tiny stone tools were found in a deposit dating back at
least 10,000 years, beneath which there was a deposit of large
chipped tools with the earliest dating back 12,700 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Copies of S. Africa's New Constitution to be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Constitutional Assembly
(CA) of South Africa is planning to launch a nationwide massive
distribution campaign of the country's new constitution in a bid
to make people aware of its significance.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's first post-apartheid constitution, drafted by
the CA after more than two-year's painstaking writing process,
was signed into law by President Nelson Mandela on December 10
last year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Johannesburg on Thursday, CA
Chairman Cyril Ramaphosa said millions of copies of the
constitution would be sent to delivery points around the country
in the largest distribution campaign ever undertaken by the Post
Office in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ramaphosa said the new constitution would mobilize and capture
the imaginations of millions and would determine significant
features of the country's political landscape.
</P>
<P>
He also said the now defunct CA had always recognized the need
to draw up a constitution which would be accessible to all South
Africans, citing the adoption of a series of measures such as
printing the constitution in all the 11 official languages and
publishing it in Braille and in a comic strip format.
</P>
<P>
About six million copies of the constitution will be
distributed to more than 11,000 distribution points throughout
the country, including schools, the defense force, the police and
correctional services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
