<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Woman With Brain Tumor Survives After Hours of Breath Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A 36-year-old woman, whose breath
stopped for five hours, has fully recovered after removal of a
brain tumor.
</P>
<P>
Huang Jiping, a farmer in Yining County in south China's
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, became totally paralysed in
January and had difficulties in breathing because of the
five-centimeter tumor.
</P>
<P>
Huang was admitted to the Guangxi Medical University hospital
on February 24. The next day her breath stopped suddenly and she
became cyanotic.
</P>
<P>
Doctors in the hospital immediately attempted a craniotomy to
take out the tumor in the great occipital foramen that pressed against
the respiration center causing the breathing to stop.
</P>
<P>
All the functions of the patient soon recovered after the
four-hour neurosurgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
