<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000-year-old Chinese Site to Qualify for World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A 5,000-year-old site in Yuhang
city in east China's Zhejiang Province, which is on the list of
state protection, has been added to a tentative list of World
Heritage sites.
</P>
<P>
Every year, three or four sites on the tentative list are
chosen for the World Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
The site covers a 24-sq-km area at Liangzhu, where the remains
of a 300,000-sq-m building used for ritual purposes, and traces of
rice-cultivating, along with high quality jade, pottery, lacquer,
and silk have been discovered.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say they value the site because it is
the largest Neolithic site ever to be found and that inscriptions
on jade and pottery found there may be the origin of Chinese
characters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
