<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Province Receives More Overseas Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Sichuan
Province has become a popular tourist destination, especially for
overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the province received 455,000
overseas tourists in 1996 who brought in 162 million U.S. dollars,
increases of more than 20 percent respectively over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan abounds in tourism resources. Out of China's 120
state-level scenic sites, 13 are here. It also has eight
historical and cultural cities, 33 key cultural sites under state
top protection, and more than 30 nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
To take advantage of these, Sichuan invested heavily in
infrastructure during the Eighth Five-Year-Plan (1991-95). In the
past five years, the province had spent 350 million yuan and used
210 million U.S. dollars in overseas funds on four
provincial-level tourism and holiday zones.
</P>
<P>
It now has more than 150 hotels that can handle overseas
tourists, and 395 travel agencies. It has also improved local
transportation conditions to attract more overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Efforts have been made to improve tourist programs and offer
more than 30 tourist routes and special themes. It has staged
eight cultural festivals, which have helped the province reach the
tourist source market in Hong Kong, Macao and Southeast Asian
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
