<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 14 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- At least two tanks appeared on the streets of the
Albanian capital Tirana tonight, apparently in an attempt to stem
the unrest gripping the country.
</P>
<P>
One tank was seen in front of President Sali Berisha's office,
and the other was patrolling the Boulevard of the Martyrs of the
Nation, where several key government institutions are located.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with political parties earlier today, Berisha
proposed that tanks be posted in front of the main government
institutions after unrest spread to the capital. Citizens today
looted a warehouse of 650 tons of flour and raided an ammunition
magazine of the security force.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the United Nations Security Council Thursday
called on all political forces in Albania to work together to
lower tension and restore stability in the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the West can find a way
to solve their dispute over NATO's eastward expansion if the West
puts Russia's interests on an equal footing with its own, the
Russian Defence Council said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The council, made up of the heads of Russian "power
ministries," such as Defense and the Interior were meeting to
prepare for next week's Russian-U.S. summit in Helsinki between
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Top of the agenda were issues relating to NATO's proposal to
let members of the former Warsaw Pact join its military alliance.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS --The Security Council Thursday expressed
concern over the slow pace of food and medical deliveries to Iraq
under the United Nation's "oil-for-food" plan.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council, while welcoming the smooth operation
concerning Iraqi oil, expresses concern regarding the humanitarian
aspect of the implementation of resolution 986," council president
Zbigniew Wlosowicz of Poland told the press.
</P>
<P>
Under Security Council Resolution 986, Iraq was allowed to sell
up to two billion U.S. dollars worth of oil. It was to be in
exchange for food and medicine to alleviate the suffering of Iraqi
people caused by the U.N. sanctions imposed since 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
