<HEADLINE> Chongqing Party Secretary on Development Strategy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The city will develop auto, metallurgical and chemical
industries as the three pillars of its economy, and build a number
of industrial zones in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River,
with an emphasis on industries supported by high and new
technologies, and on the service industry consisting of commerce
and trade, finance, tourism, real estate and information, he
added.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamental way for Chongqing to accomplish its historical
mission is to add momentum to rural economic development by giving
full play to the central role of the cities," he said, adding that
Chongqing aims to develop itself into a center of commerce and
trade, finance, science, education and information, a hub of
transportation and telecom services, and a modern industrial base
in the upper reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
"We will also build Chongqing into a metropolis surrounded by a
number of booming towns and cities of medium or small sizes," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Chongqing's regional advantages and superiorities,
he said that the city is located where two regional economies --
the Yangtze River economy and the southwest China economy -- meet,
and that the construction of the Three Gorges Project has provided
a huge potential market and a capital market of more than 100
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
"In history, Chongqing was an industrial and commercial center
of the Yangtze River upper reaches and southwest China. If
Chongqing develops well, the economy of entire southwest China
will be invigorated," he asserted.
</P>
<P>
The new status of Chongqing has already attracted much
attention from foreign investors, and Japan is actively seeking
participation in the city's telecom infrastructure construction
and the upgrading of old industries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Describing Chongqing as the sole metropolis in the world that
has an excessively large rural population, he said that the
elevation of the city to the status of a municipality is China's
one more experiment on economic and administrative restructuring.
</P>
<P>
"We will establish a small but efficient government staffed by
competent people and do our work well so as to live up to the
expectations of the central authorities and the people," he
pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
