<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Resources to Lend Wing to Chongqing's Economic Takeoff (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The southwestern metropolis of
Chongqing has a wide range of representative industrial products,
from a tiny piece of white porcelain to a huge aluminum ingot
weighing several hundred kilograms.
</P>
<P>
These products have at least one thing in common: they are all
results of the exploitation of rich local natural resources.
Technicians in the Zhaofeng Porcelain Co., a Chongqing-Hong Kong
joint venture, claimed that one important reason for the
popularity the company's products on domestic and global markets
is the use of local pure natural gas in the firing process.
</P>
<P>
The China Southwestern Aluminum Fabricating Plant in Chongqing,
one of the country's largest manufacturers of aluminum products
with an annual production capacity of 260,000 tons, has owed its
development to local bauxite reserves of 29 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, the largest city in southwest China, has just become
the country's fourth centrally-administered municipality following
Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
With an expanded territory of 82,000 sq km that covers the
whole eastern part of Sichuan Province, Chongqing is now the
world's largest city, and boasts abundant natural resources.
</P>
<P>
"Initial prospecting showed that Chongqing has more than 40
kinds of mineral resources, including large quantities of natural
gas, bauxite, salt, strontium and limestone," said Li Deshui, vice
mayor of Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
The natural gas field in east Sichuan is China's largest at
present, with long-term deposits of more than 300 billion cubic
meters. Chongqing also has deposits of more than 300 billion tons
of salt, close to two million tons of strontium, and two billion
tons of limestone.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, mountains and hills of Chongqing also contain more
than three billion tons of coal, and a great deal of other mineral
resources, such as manganese, mercury and marble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
