<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou To Register Migrant Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- In order to reduce
unemployment, the Guangzhou municipal government will restrict
migrant workers from working, the city's vice mayor said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities will register all migrant workers and issue a work
permit. The computerized network would prevent outsiders from
working in the prosperous city, south China's Guangdong Province
near Hong Kong, Wu Liang, the vice mayor, said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Wu also said his city should not exile migrant workers to solve
unemployment. The lack of workers, especially capable ones,
requires the economic hub be open to as many workers as possible.
</P>
<P>
A long-held view is that the too many migrant workers are
responsible for the city's increasing unemployment, so many city
residents suggest the city should remove migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
Wu has foreclosed this possibility to limit the migrant labor
force, citing his city will handle it in line with the law of the
socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
An authoritative statistic shows that the city had more than
50,000 laid-off workers at the end of last year, with the
unemployment rate at 2.28 percent. From 1997 on, Guangzhou
endeavors to put the unemployment ceiling at 60,000.
</P>
<P>
Ten vocation training centers, under the guidance of the
municipal government, will provide an opportunity for workers,
both in-service and out-of-work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
