<HEADLINE> Mass Evacuation of Foreigners from Albania Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Governments of many countries have
begun evacuating their nationals in Albania since Thursday when
unrest and anarchy were engulfing Albania.
</P>
<P>
The United States has sent four military helicopters into
Tirana and evacuated 50 Americans, most of them children, to
U.S. ships standing offshore.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns
said that 170 Americans, mostly dependents of U.S. Embassy workers
and non-essential staff, were being evacuated under the escort of
U.S. Marines.
</P>
<P>
Up to 2,000 American citizens are in Albania, Burns said,
adding that the evacuation will continue for days.
</P>
<P>
Italy also used helicopters to rescue 330 Italians and 70 other
foreigners to its warships in the Adriatic. As estimated, there
are 1,300 Italians in Albania.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many other countries used land routes for
evacuations Thursday as Tirana's main airport closed after
Albanians who had looted guns began firing into the air.
</P>
<P>
Britain organized a pullout of more than 120 foreigners in a
convoy of vehicles from Tirana to the port of Durres, 40
kilometers west of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a final warning to British nationals to leave Albania,
the British Foreign Office ordered the British embassy in Tirana
to organize another convoy for the evacuation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Moscow said that it had a specific plan to withdraw Russian
nationals from Albania.
</P>
<P>
Now, the United States and other NATO countries were meeting in
Brussels, to coordinate the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been in the grip of unrest since January after the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
The protest turned violent two weeks ago as rebels looted
weapons from army depots. Several cities in southern Albania are
now controlled by rebels who are threatening to move onto the
capital.
</P>
<P>
Tirana itself has also witnessed growing unrest as mobs looted
a warehouse of 650 tons of flour on Thursday and raided security
force depots in search of guns.
</P>
<P>
Albanian President Sali Berisha on Thursday decided to deploy
tanks in front of the main institutions in the country and called
on the Western European Union to provide military assistance to
Tirana to restore order in the country which is verging on civil
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
