<HEADLINE> World's Longest Bridge Tender Open to S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- South African
bridge-builders are being invited to tender for the construction
of the world's longest road bridge, local daily the Star reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The Proposed 41 km bridge will link Colonia in Uruguay to
Buenos Aires in Argentina over the Rio de la Plata River in South
America.
</P>
<P>
The Star quoted Jose Luis Aldabalde, Uruguay ambassador to
South Africa, as saying that the construction of the bridge was
part of a joint developments program agreed by members of the
Mercosur Economic Union, which was recently established in
Montevideo, capital of Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur links Uruguay, Argentina, Brazil and Paraguay, with
Chile as an associate member, in a common market which is
expected to revitalise the economies of all countries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Aldabalde said the embassies of Argentina and Uruguay, on
behalf of the Bilateral Commission Bridge Buenos Aires-Colonia,
extended an invitation to interested South African companies in
the pre-qualification stage leading to the participation in an
international bid for the design, construction, operation and
maintenance concession.
</P>
<P>
The present world's longest bridge is the Second Lake
Pontchartrain Causeway in Louisiana, United States, which
stretches for 38.4 km.
</P>
<P>
The existing longest combined railway and road bridge is the
Seto-Ohashi double-decker bridge in Japan, covering a distance of
12.3 km.
</P>
<P>
The tallest bridge over water is the Golden Gate bridge in San
Francisco, which is 227 metres high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
