<HEADLINE> Arafat Offers Condolences Over Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat has telephoned Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu
to offer his condolences over the death of seven Israeli
schoolgirls in Thursday's shooting near Israeli-Jordanian
border, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who had reportedly refused to talk to Netanyahu in the
past week, made the phone call Thursday night to offer his
condolences to the families of the victims, who were killed by a
Jordanian soldier in Naharayim on the Jordanian side of northern
Jordan Valley.
</P>
<P>
While expressing his appreciation of the condolence call,
Netanyahu said that leaders shared heavy responsibility not to
stir up violence and refrain from declarations that could lead to
violence.
</P>
<P>
Israeli leaders indirectly blamed the Thursday tragedy on the
recent strong criticism of Israeli policies from Jordanian King
Hussein, who wrote a harsh-worded letter to Netanyahu warning that
his policies could lead to bloodshed and destroy the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Arafat, Netanyahu repeated that there could be
differences of opinion, but there should be no room for talks
of violence. "If there is agreement on that, the results could be
productive," he said.
</P>
<P>
Before the shooting incident, the Palestinian side had been
warning against violence as a result of Israel's recent decisions
to build a settlement in Har Homa and to close four Palestinian
offices in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who met with Israeli opposition Labor Party's lawmaker
Uzi Baram late Thursday, said he was willing to meet Netanyahu to
discuss ways of defusing current tension if such a meeting could
produce practical results.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein, who cut short his visit to Spain after the
shooting and returned home Thursday night, also called Netanyahu
on the plane to offer his condolences to the victims. In a news
conference held at Amman Airport, Hussein condemned the shooting
as "a slur on all of us" and "a vile crime."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that he was willing to pay a visit to the
families of the victims and would meet Netanyahu shortly.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti had
telephoned Netanyahu, President Ezer Weizman and Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai to express condolences. Jordanian Crown Prince
Hassan held talks with Mordechai at the site of shooting to
coordinate efforts to investigate the incident.
</P>
<P>
It is feared that the latest incident could set back the
already soured ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite the signing of the 1994 peace treaty, widespread
anti-Israeli sentiment still can be felt in the Hashemite kingdom
because of the lack of benefits from the peace-making. Moreover,
the sentiment has been repeatedly fueled by the crises in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
