<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Scholar Says Dalai Lama Violates Human Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Puncog's family used to live near the Johkang Monastery in the
center of Lhasa. At that time, the street in front of the
monastery was full of beggars, who often died of hunger or from
the cold. Sometimes, their bodies were bitten by dogs, or the
head, hands and hearts were used in religious ceremonies for
nobles or officials, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
"Serfs were regarded by their masters as talking animals," he
said. "Homeless serfs would become beggars, and what they could
look forward to was death. That was the human rights situation in
Tibet under the Dalai Lama's rule."
</P>
<P>
Like other Tibetan commoners, Puncog's father and mother served
different masters, and were badly bullied and exploited.
</P>
<P>
At that time, there were two courts in Lhasa, which were
located alongside a prison. Prisoners had to eat leftover qingke
(a kind of highland barley), and were bound by iron chains and saw
little sunlight.
</P>
<P>
"The history of old Tibet was one written in the blood and
tears of serfs," Puncog Cering said. "Those days are gone
forever. Now Tibetans have equal rights in politics and the
economy, in production, and in daily life. Everyone is equal under
the law."
</P>
<P>
In Tibet's prime, there were 10 million people. But when Tibet
was liberated in the 1950s, there were only about a million,
because many young people had been forced into monasteries by the
government. Moreover, medical conditions for ordinary people were
extremely poor.
</P>
<P>
In old Lhasa, only a few people could afford medical care, and
there were only half a dozen private schools for children from
rich families. Now over 70 percent of Tibetan kids are able to
attend school in bright and spacious classrooms.
</P>
<P>
When Tibet was liberated in 1951, the average life expectancy
of Tibetans was only 35 years, now it has gone up to 65, and the
survival rate of babies has risen from 30 percent to 95 percent,
according to Puncog Cering.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetan Scholar Says Dalai Lama Violates Human Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Dalai Lama had an extremely
poor human rights record himself when he was in Tibet and is
hardly qualified to talk about human rights, a noted Tibetan
professor told Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
The laws which the Dalai Lama used in ruling Tibet before
fleeing the plateau region showed that the ruling class willfully
trampled on the rights of the vast majority of serfs, said Puncog
Cering, president of the Tibet branch of the China Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
Puncog Cering has just compiled "A Collection of Laws in Tibet
in the Past," and is now busy translating the Tibetan into
Chinese, at the request of Soochow University of Taiwan, where it
will be translated into English.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan version was published by Tibetan Classical Books
Publishing House and the Chinese and English versions will be
published by Soochow University by the end of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
The law as practiced under the Dalai Lama made it clear that
humans were divided into nine ranks, and serfs and common women
were at the lowest levels.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of a blacksmith or butcher who was murdered could
only get a piece of flax rope as compensation. In the case of a
common woman, the compensation was 10 liang (about 11 ounces) of
silver. But, compensation in the case of a slain noble was 120
liang of silver, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
Serfs had no freedom of speech. If several serfs were found
complaining about the government, they would be punished. If one
argued with someone superior in rank, he would be arrested.
</P>
<P>
Those caught stealing the property of a living Buddha or of
officials, or caught fighting with their master could have their
eyes or tongue cut out or hands cut off, or could be hurled down a
cliff or into a river, according to the law.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that the prerequisite for formulating these laws
was protection of the interests of the class of owners of serfs,"
Puncog Cering said.
</P>
<P>
"In the process of compiling the book, I have become to deeply
understand that the laws in old Tibet were the cruelest in the
world, and did not respect human rights at all," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Denies Blocking Burundi Relief Cargo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has refuted
reports that it was holding humanitarian supplies destined for
Burundi at the Dar es Salaam port, saying the sanctions imposed
on Bujumbura did not cover humanitarian supplies.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Minister for Foreign Affairs and International
Co-operation, Jakaya Kikwete, said here on Thursday that
thousands of tonnes of various supplies for Burundi have passed
through Tanzania between last July and February this year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister added over 10,000 tonnes of fertilizer,
1,200 litres of fuel, 1,000 tonnes of medical supplies and over
5,000 tonnes of maize, beans, vegetable oil, rice, biscuits and
other food items passed through Tanzania during the period.
</P>
<P>
He noted other items such as vehicles, clothing, plastic sheet
and jerry cans also passed through Tanzania from various sources
including the United Nations High Commission for Refugees
(UNHCR), UN system and Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs).
</P>
<P>
Kikwete further said apart from the petroleum products which
passes through Tanzania, other quantities pass through Kigali. He
said the government was not responsible for any delay, but the
individual suppliers and carriers. 
