<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building New North-South Canal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China has been working on a new
415-km north-south canal parallel to the historic Grand Canal, in
east China's Jiangsu Province, starting at Tongzhou in Nantong
City and ending at Ganyu County in Lianyungang City.
</P>
<P>
According to Xiao Yehong, an official in charge of the project,
fifty km of the canal have been completed since work started in
1993, and dredge work has started on 24.5 km.
</P>
<P>
Xiao called the new canal a "little brother" of the
Beijing-Hangzhou Grand Canal, which is 1,794 km long and more than
a thousand years old.
</P>
<P>
The official said that new canal would have the same width
(60m) and same depth (4m) as the old one, but will have certain
advantages. It can not only handle 1,000 dwt craft, but can also
divert water from the Yangtze River for irrigating northern areas
of Jiangsu at a rate of 100 cu m per second.
</P>
<P>
In addition to improving northern Jiangsu's flood water and
irrigation water handling capacity, the canal will play an
important role in dredging of port areas along the east coast, and
in supplying water for power stations, including the planned
nuclear power station in Lianyungang City.
</P>
<P>
The new canal will be built in three stages. Work has started
on the 245-km middle section. The project is one of China's major
water control projects, and is expected to cost 1.8 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China's Province Makes Progress in Reemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- More than 240,000 unemployed
people in central China's Hunan Province have found new jobs
thanks to a provincial reemployment project.
</P>
<P>
There are 600,000 surplus workers in state-owned enterprises,
accounting for 18 percent of all workers and staff. The problem is
that they have not adapted easily to the new competitive situation
in looking for jobs because of a lack of skills.
</P>
<P>
So, the city of Zhuzhou took the lead in starting a
reemployment project by setting up training centers in the early
1990s, where laid-off workers are asked to go for technical
training while seeking jobs by themselves. In average, they can
get a monthly income of about 400 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Provincial labor departments are spreading the practice and
want to create a competitive environment, in which unemployed
people can learn practical techniques to prepare themselves.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand workers lost their jobs when the Xiangtan
Textile, Printing and Dyeing Plant, a large stated-owned
enterprise, saw production orders fall. So, the people were given
training in dressmaking, marketing, accounting, printing, and
electrical appliance repairs.
</P>
<P>
As a result, more than 80 percent of them have found new jobs,
and many have learned a new versatility. "We have two hands to
rely on and it is not so difficult to find new jobs as long as we
master new skills," said one.
</P>
<P>
Now, about 160 of these centers are open to the jobless, and
welfare departments provided over 70 million yuan in loans last
year to finance the reemployment projects.
</P>
<P>
The project has also been extended to rural areas. Labor
management offices were opened in half the province's 2,410
villages by the end of 1996 to help with the orderly movement of
the rural surplus labor force and to help ease the pressure on
urban areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
