<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Starts Large-scale River Pollution Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan province
has launched a large scale project to fight pollution in the
Xiangjiang river, and plans to improve the qualities of water
flows considerably in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The river is the province's main water way, with the river
valley covering 92,500 square kilometers, or 40 percent of the
province's entire landspace. The river affects 60 percent of the
province's population and 70 percent of its economic operations.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, however, as the local economy developed,
pollution became an increasingly serious problem.
</P>
<P>
Starting in the 1970s, the province began a series of studies
of the valley's environment, said Liu Jiucheng, vice-director of
the provincial Environmental Protection Bureau, and it has spent
over three billion yuan (375 million US dollars) on pollution
control there since the '80s.
</P>
<P>
"We have a special fund of 60 million yuan annually for
pollution control," Liu noted.
</P>
<P>
A number of factories with serious pollution problems, such as
the Zhuzhou Smeltery and the Xiangtan Steel Plant have spent a
great deal on pollution control projects. As a result, the heavy
metal and arsenic content of the river have dropped by 30 percent
and 60 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The province is determined to enhance efforts at combatting
pollution, and plans to spent 2.7 billion yuan on pollution
control during the 1996-2000 period, with some 794 million yuan to
be spent this year.
</P>
<P>
The province is planning on reducing the heavy metal content by
80 percent and the solid matter by 60 percent in the river by the
end of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
