<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Owned Retailer Forced to Resume Cuban Pyjamas Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.-owned retail giant
Wal-Mart Canada Ltd. said today it will resume selling Cuban-made
pyjamas this weekend, two-weeks after pulling them off its shelves
across Canada.
</P>
<P>
The about-face came after a comprehensive review and discussion
with customers, legal advisers and the Canadian government, the
retailer said.
</P>
<P>
The move "reflects our commitment to meet the expectations of
the Canadian marketplace," it was quoted as saying by reports here.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the retailer decided to remove the Cuban-made
pyjamas from all its 136 Canadian stores after a customer
complaint in the city of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
The removal conforms with the U.S. Helms-Burton law that
penalizes countries and companies that do business with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
However, it comes into direct conflict with Canada's Foreign
Extraterritorial Measures Act, which forbids companies here from
complying in any way with the U.S. anti-Cuba law.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian legislation threatens companies with fines
equivalent to those in the Helms-Burton law, which has penalties
up to one million U.S. dollars for companies doing business with
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government said last week that it was looking at
whether Wal-Mart violated any Canadian laws by pulling the pyjamas
from store shelves.
</P>
<P>
"It's something we are monitoring," a spokesman for the Justice
Department said at that time.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin also warned businesses not to bow
to the U.S. anti-Cuban law and "act according to Canadian ethics."
</P>
<P>
In addition, a group of Winnipeggers staged a protest last
weekend at a Wal-Mart store, strongly condemning the retailer's
decision to stop selling Cuban-made pyjamas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
