<HEADLINE> Star American Skier Lindh Retires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- World downhill champion Hilary
Lindh announced her retirement on Thursday, ending a 13-year
sparkling career and leaving behind her in the U.S. ski team a
great vacuum.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old from Juneau, Alaska, has just experienced a
remarkable final season in her career, rallying from a 32nd-place
finish in the season opener to a world championship a month ago at
Sestriere, Italy.
</P>
<P>
Yet Lindh failed to fulfill her dream of ending her career with
a triumph at Vail, Colorado, site of a World Cup victory in 1995.
On Wednesday's World Cup finals downhill event she only ended up
in ninth place.
</P>
<P>
Frequently at her best in important races, she won a silver
medal at the 1992 Olympics, bronze at the 1996 world championships
and, finally, gold at the 1997 worlds -- stamping herself the most
successful American downhill skier in major events.
</P>
<P>
Along the way, she won three World Cup races, a world junior
championship and universal respect as a tough competitor
reflecting her Alaskan heritage.
</P>
<P>
Her departure leaves a gaping void on a U.S. downhill squad
decimated this season by injuries to three of its stars, Picabo
Street, Tommy Moe and Kyle Rasmussen, and the lingering effects of
a 1995 injury to AJ Kitt.
</P>
<P>
She will compete next week in the U.S. national championships
at Sugarloaf, Maine, then enroll for the spring term at the
University of Utah, where she will study biology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
