<HEADLINE> Jiangsu Province Leads In Industrial Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
ranked first among all provinces in China in gross industrial
output 1996, according to the provincial statistics bureau.
</P>
<P>
The province generated 10 percent of the country's total
industrial output and 277.7 billion yuan in added value, also
accounting for 10 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu, which has a population of about 71 million, scored a
GDP of 605.7 billion yuan (72.98 billion U.S. dollars) in 1996, a
rise of 12.2 percent over 1995. The per capita GDP stood at 1,026
US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu is one of the eastern coast areas that have had fast
economic expansion and a higher degree of opening-up to the
outside world in the past several years. By 1995, the province
had 459,000 industrial and manufacturing enterprises, with assets
reaching 804.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Living standards have improved for residents thanks to fast
economic growth and a lower population growth rate of 5.53 per
thousand.
</P>
<P>
The average income for urban residents was 4,689 yuan and for
those in rural areas 3,029 yuan last year, both exceeding the
State Statistics Bureau's index of a comfortable life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
