<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Gasification Project Starts in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Construction work on a major
coal gasification project which will benefit some 1.6 million
residents of three cities in Henan Province began in Yima Coal
Mine recently.
</P>
<P>
According to an official in charge, the gasification will be
done in a large pit yard and gasified coal will be sent to the
cities of Zhengzhou, Luoyang, and Sanmenxia in central China.
</P>
<P>
The project will require the building of a factory at the
source, and of long-distance pipelines, and will have a daily
production capacity of 1.2 million cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 2.89 billion yuan (about 348 million
U.S. dollars), 62.98 million dollars of which will be covered by
loans provided by the Australian government. The loans will be
used to buy key technology and equipment from Germany and the
United States. The project will be finished by the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Henan is China's second largest coal producer. The gasification
facilities are considered to be a project in the public interest,
especially for reducing the use of coal in urban areas and
improving the environment. These cities will decrease the volume
of pollutants discharged each year when residents and industrial
manufacturers change from coal to gas. It is especially
significant for protecting many cultural relics in Luoyang, which
used to be the capital for nine dynasties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
