<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China's State-owned Enterprise Revitalizing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUOYANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The China No.1 Tractor
Engineering and Machinery Corporation has maintained a high-speed
increase in its economic returns for the past two years, an
encouraging sign for financially-troubled state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The company, with more than 40,000 workers, realized a total
sales volume worth 4.31 billion yuan in 1996, up 30.6 percent from
the year before.
</P>
<P>
It is the largest of its kind in China and a major contributor
to the country's agricultural mechanization.
</P>
<P>
The Luoyang No.1 Tractor Plant, a state-owned backbone
enterprise affiliated with the corporation, experienced ups and
downs in its reforms and suffered a record deficit in 1994,
despite its dominant 60 percent share of the domestic tractor
market in the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Seeking solutions, the company designated four of its branch
plants to set up foreign-funded joint ventures, in a bid to form a
new management mechanism compatible with the modern enterprise
system.
</P>
<P>
The corporation authorized its subordinates to act as legal
persons in competition on the market.
</P>
<P>
It reduced the staff of more than 4,000 and implemented the
contract system in an effort to bring workers' initiative into
full play.
</P>
<P>
The measures paid off: the company earned 260 million yuan of
profit and tax in 1996, an increase of 72.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The formerly clumsy caterpillar tractors have been transformed
by new designs, forming a series of new products widely praised in
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The corporation is now able to manufacture road rollers,
excavators and trucks for both civilian and military purposes.
</P>
<P>
It now has product orders valued at more than four billion
yuan.  enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
