<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment for Shanghai Down in January, February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The number of overseas-funded
projects and contractual investment they entailed both decreased
slightly in the first two months of this year, as compared with
the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that by the end of February, Shanghai,
the largest metropolitan business center in China, had more than
16,000 overseas-funded projects, involving pledged foreign
investment of 45.9 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In January and February, the number of industrial projects
accounted for 63 percent of the total funded by overseas
businessmen. Real estate and public undertakings take up 13
percent, followed by the sectors of transportation, posts,
telecommunications, building, and commerce.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was the biggest investor, with the number of Hong
kong-funded projects reaching 31 percent of the total. In line
behind Hong Kong were Japan, Taiwan, the United States, and
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
More than ten billion US dollars of overseas funds has flown
into Shanghai annually in the past three years, sources
say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
