<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backward South Chinese Area Seeing Speedier Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, one of the country's less developed areas, had
nearly 11 percent growth in its GDP last year, even after being
hit by the biggest flood of the century.
</P>
<P>
The growth is the result of greater efforts to develop more
profitable projects, bringing regional industrial output last year
to 16 percent more than the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The region had record grain output last year, with an increase
of 580,000 tons over 1995. Investment from overseas also rose by
nearly four percent to one billion US dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The region had more than 14.4 billion yuan in revenues last
year, up eight percent from 1995, and average per capita income in
urban areas reached 4,400 yuan, and 1,680 yuan in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Growth of the retail and consumer price indexes was held to
around 4.5 percent and 6.5 percent in 1996, respectively, much
lower than the previous year's figures of 16.4 percent and 18.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Local economic reforms, centered on state-owned enterprises,
dealt with taxes, finances, investment, foreign trade, and social
security and helped boost the region's economic growth in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
