<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book on General History of Hui Ethnic People Published </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, March 14 (Xinhua) -- China's first history book of
the Hui ethnic group was recently published by the People's
Publishing House of the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly nine million Hui people in the country who
live in more than 95 percent of the Chinese counties, with large
communities in the Ningxia and Xinjiang autonomous regions, and
Gansu, Henan and Hebei provinces.
</P>
<P>
The "History of China's Hui People" was compiled by historian
Qiu Shusen and contains more than 800,000 Chinese characters. It
details the political, economic, cultural and religious progress
as well as the folklore of the Hui people from ancient periods up
to the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Ancestors of the Hui people during the Tang and Song dynasties,
from the seventh to 13th centuries, were mainly Arabs and
Persians, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
In the 14th century, the number of Moslem Tujue (Turk) people
exceeded that of Arabs and Persians, and more Moslems came from
south China, southeast China and even Africa.
</P>
<P>
In later generations, Moslem ancestors helped many people of
the Han, Uygur and Mongolian ethnic groups convert to Islam, and
residence rights of Moslems were recognized by feudal governments
in ancient China, the book says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
