<HEADLINE> Hebei to Boost Non-Governmental Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 14 (Xinhua) -- By the turn of the century,
north China's Hebei Province will have set up 8,000
non-governmental enterprises, with annual revenues expected to
reach 15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities predict the firms' output value attributed to
new and advanced technology will account for more than 30 percent
of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goal, Hebei will adopt a series of preferential
policies for non-governmental enterprises. College graduates will
be given the same treatment at the businesses as employees of
state-run units.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has been boosting efforts to develop non-governmental
enterprises since 1994, and presently has more than 3,000 such
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's General Qualities in Inner Mongolia Improving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Eradicating illiteracy and
improving production skills, women in north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region have their general qualities greatly upgraded.
</P>
<P>
Women in the region, which has the country's largest acreage of
grassland, produce great wealth from farm crops, animal husbandry,
processing industries and a "courtyard economy".
</P>
<P>
With women playing a major role in developing the courtyard
economy, which includes animal-breeding, cash crop cultivation,
and workshops in or near courtyards, it produced 1.3 billion yuan
last year, accounting for 30 percent of local family incomes.
</P>
<P>
For the past 11 years, the region has had a campaign to get
women to learn more and acquire skills.
</P>
<P>
Ninety percent of the region's women received training during
the period and 100,000 of them were awarded the title of
technician.
</P>
<P>
The move was also responsible for the rising of a large number
of women officials. According to statistics, 643 women in the
region have been promoted to posts at or above the county level.
</P>
<P>
As people in the region grew more aware of the importance of
education, relations between neighbors and between family members
have become more harmonious. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breast Cancer on Rise in Indian Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Breast cancer is on the rise in
Indian cities, Ministry for Health and Family Welfare sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the leading causes of death from cancer in women
between 35-54 years of age. In New Delhi, capital of India, it is
the most common form of cancer among women.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Tata Memorial Hospital in Bombay recorded an
upward trend in breast cancer which now equals the high rate of
uterine cancer in the city.
</P>
<P>
According to a report of the World Health Organization (WHO),
worldwide deaths from breast cancer will rise to 500,000 by the
year 2000 and almost a fifth of these will be in the Indian
subcontinent.
</P>
<P>
Though the incidence of breast cancer continues to swell,
awareness and information about tumors is low. Besides, the social
stigma attached to the dreaded disease also deters even educated
people from seeking timely medical help. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Natural Gas from Northwest China to Reach Beijing in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Natural gas from northwest China
will be channeled through a pipeline to Beijing beginning
September 30.
</P>
<P>
The entire project has been under construction for nearly seven
years, costing six billion yuan (722.9 million US dollars),
according to officials of Beijing's municipal government.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, a total of 1.08 million Beijing
households will be using natural gas, up from the current 400,000.
</P>
<P>
In the city's eight districts, 54,000 stoves still burn coal,
and the sulphur dioxide and dust they discharge are the main cause
of Beijing's air pollution.
</P>
<P>
According to arrangements set by the State Planning Commission,
from 1998 to 2000, gas fields in Shaanxi and Gansu provinces and
the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region will provide Beijing with 1.5
billion cubic meters of natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing municipal government has scheduled that all
coal-burning stoves inside the third ring-road of Beijing will be
burning natural gas in four years.
</P>
<P>
Medium and small coal-burning furnaces and heat-supplying
plants scattered in the urban areas will be using gas
gradually. Meanwhile, the amount of coal used in industrial
production will be cut down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
