<HEADLINE> Tanks Deployed in Tirana to Stem Unrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- At least two tanks appeared on the
streets of the Albanian capital Tirana tonight, apparently in an
attempt to stem the unrest gripping the country.
</P>
<P>
One tank was seen in front of President Sali Berisha's office,
and the other was patrolling the Boulevard of the Martyrs of the
Nation, where several key government institutions are located.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with political parties earlier today, Berisha
proposed that tanks be posted in front of the main government
institutions after unrest spread to the capital. Citizens today
looted a warehouse of 650 tons of flour and raided an ammunition
magazine of the security force.
</P>
<P>
The unrest spread out earlier in the day when some 300 people
looted the barracks in Bajram Curri, a town about 200 kilometers
northeast of Tirana, and took away hundreds of assault rifles.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, anti-government rebels seized weapons from a
military base near Elbasan, only 55 kilometers from Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The country is thrown into anarchy after two weeks of
clashes. The authorities have appealed for foreign military
intervention to help end the crisis but so far no affirmative
response has been made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
