<HEADLINE> Peace Talks on CHT in Bangladesh End Inconclusively </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The tribal delegation left here
this morning with empty hands as the two-day peace talks on the
Chittagong hill tracts (CHT) in southern Bangladesh ended
inconclusively Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Both sides, however, agreed to meet again on April 30. And it
was also agreed in the meeting that the existing ceasefire would
be extended unto June 30.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, it was thought that the two sides would reach an
agreement this time to resolve the decades-old insurgency problem
in the CHT, but this fourth round of talks ended without any
agreement.
</P>
<P>
"We had cordial talks and agreed to meet for another round of
dialogue on April 30," said head of the government delegation Abu
Hasnat Abdullah, who declined to reveal details of the talks.
</P>
<P>
According to meeting sources, the talks were progressing on the
desired direction on Wednesday but on Thursday, the talks mainly
concentrated on Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's address in
Chittagong where she said that the Muslim settlers would not be
withdrawn from the hill tracts.
</P>
<P>
The tribal leaders told the meeting that it would be useless to
continue a dialogue when the government was not even considering
doing anything regarding the Muslim settlers from the plains.
</P>
<P>
They said that the withdrawal of settlers was a major issue
towards a peace agreement. The hill people will not accept any
peace agreement without resolving the issue in any form.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached earlier this month, the
tribal refugees in the Indian state of Tripura would be returning
home from March 28. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
