<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Industrial Production Index Up In January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's industrial
production index, which measures the rate of change in the
production of industrial commodities over time, rose 11.9 percent
for January 1997 in comparison with that of the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The January 1997 index was 253.0 against 226.1 in January 1996
and the first month's industrial production index was also 1.4
percent higher from 249.5 in December last year, according to data
released by the Department of Statistics here today.
</P>
<P>
All the three divisions under the industrial sector reflected
an upward movement with the mining division rising 6.1 percent to
163.2 from 153.8, the manufacturing division gaining 12.9 percent
to 297.5 from 263.5 and the electricity division increasing 20.0
percent to 295.2 from 246.0 during the period under review.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department, the main contributors to the rise
in the index of the mining division between January last year to
the first month of 1997 was the increase in crude oil index to
147.2 from 141.6 and natural gas to 285.9 from 250.5. However, the
index for tin fell 39.2 percent to 16.6 from 27.3.
</P>
<P>
In the manufacturing division, 18 of the 19 major groups
recorded higher indexes for January 1997 against the same month of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Transport equipment recorded the biggest leap to 399.3 from
301.3 in the first month of 1996, followed by iron and steel
basic industries to 352.0 from 279.7, non-metallic mineral
products to 357.0 from 287.0, industrial chemicals to 246.0 from
200.9 and wood, wood and cork products except furniture to 260.0
from 214.0.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco manufactures increased to 122.5 from 103.1,
non-ferrous metal basic industries to 186.6 from 161.3, food
manufacturing to 168.7 from 145.8, crude oil refineries to 227.3
from 197.5, electrical machinery, apparatus, appliances and
supplies to 445.2 from 402.2 and beverage industries to 217.5 from
197.1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
