<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Passes Bill on EU Border Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Greek parliament today
approved in principle a bill protecting individual liberty and
privacy, which will facilitate Greece's participation in a
European Union (EU) agreement on border control.
</P>
<P>
The parliament voted 132 to 89 for the bill, paving the way for
Greece's entrance into the agreement, which lifts passport
controls among EU members and shares police data.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Costas Simitis, responding to opposition
criticism, said the bill would protect citizens, strengthen
democracy and allow better transparency in the flow of information.
</P>
<P>
Greece is one of the few members of the 15-nation EU which has
not yet ratified the Schengen Agreement, aimed at creating a
border-free EU. Britain and Ireland have not signed up to the pact.
</P>
<P>
The Netherlands, the current holder of the EU presidency,
proposed last month to bring the deal into a new European Union
treaty which is currently under negotiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
