<HEADLINE> Ukraine Suspends Salaries in Government Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Pavel
Lazarenko authorized the Financial Ministry at a cabinet meeting
today to suspend salaries in all ministries and provincial
governments.
</P>
<P>
Salaries of cabinet members and organizations were also
suspended.
</P>
<P>
The suspension was made because all the ministries and
provincial governments had failed to submit the first quarter's
budget plan to the Financial Ministry before the deadline of March
10, Lazarenko said.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government's 1997 budget plan is still waiting
for approval by parliament. So President Leonid Kuchma ordered, on
February 28, that all ministries and provincial governments,
including the cities of Kiev and Sevastopal, should work out the
first quarter's budget before March 10.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian economy has remained stagnant since the beginning
of the year. About 40 percent of industrial enterprises were
running in the red in January and February. Financial income was
2.64 billion hryvnas (about 1.4 billion dollars) in the first two
months, only 80 percent of the estimated earnings.
</P>
<P>
A survey issued by the World Bank shows that one-third of
Ukrainians, or 17 million residents, are living under the poverty
line.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian government is at its wits' end on how to tackle
continuous strikes over wage arrears, and how to increase budget
income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
