<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Urges End of Tension in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council this evening called on all political forces in
Albania to work together to lower tension and restore stability in
the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
Council President Zbigniew Wlosowicz, of Poland, said the
Security Council expressed its deep concern about the
deteriorating situation in Albania.
</P>
<P>
"It urges all concerned to refrain from hostilities and acts of
violence, and to cooperate with diplomatic efforts to reach a
peaceful solution to the crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council called upon the parties involved to
continue the political dialogue and to live up to the commitments
they made on Sunday, said the statement read by Wlosowicz.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached Sunday between President Berisha and
10 opposition parties, an interim coalition government was formed
to stem the unrest and oversee early general elections in June.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council discussed over the past two days two
letters presented by the permanent representatives of Albania and
Italy, which asked for international assistance to Albania.
</P>
<P>
The Council called upon the parties not to impede the provision
of humanitarian assistance to the civilian population, and
emphasized the importance of keeping open all means of
communication in the country, the president said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. body also stressed the importance of regional
stability and fully supported the diplomatic efforts of the
international community, in particular efforts by the European
continent, to find a peaceful solution to the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unrest began to sweep Albania after the collapse of pyramid
investment schemes in which hundreds of thousands of Albanians
lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
Despite the formation of the interim government, looting still
plagues the country and a growing number of cities were thrown
into anarchy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
