<HEADLINE> Nepal's Garment Makers Want Timely Export Permits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Garment industry of Nepal
is running into huge losses due to the central bank's failure to
issue export permission in time, local industrialists said today.
</P>
<P>
Nepal Rastra Bank, the central bank, is not ready to provide
permits for ready-made garment exports to the United States even
when American buyers are trying to exact price concessions for the
delivery delays, the official news agency RSS quoted exporters as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The exporters said that they are now willing to sell at the
reduced prices and suffer a loss.
</P>
<P>
The United States is the largest buyer of Nepalese garments,
which bought nearly 90 million US dollars worth of garments from
Nepal last year.
</P>
<P>
Nepal's garment industry employs some 100,000 workers across
the country and ranks second among the country's exporting
industries after the carpet manufacturing industry.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Satyendra Pyara Shrestha told a meeting
of local garment industrialists here Thursday that there will be
no more delays in providing export permissions.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged that his bank will extend cooperation in the
development and expansion of the garment industry, which serves as
a major foreign exchange earner of the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
