<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA-ATA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Military maneuvers carried out
under NATO's Partnership for Peace program should be aimed at
improving the effectiveness of peacekeeping missions in areas of
conflict, delegates at a meeting on military exercises in Central
Asia said today.
</P>
<P>
Kazakh news agency reported that the meeting, organized by the
Kazakh defense ministry, was attended by representatives from
Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Uzbekistan, the United States, Russia,
Ukraine, Turkey, Denmark, Lithuania and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, presided over by Kazakh first Deputy Defense
Minister Fedor Sherbakov, discussed the "Central Asian
Peacekeeping Camp-97'" military exercises scheduled for mid
September, which will be carried out in Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Turkey and Denmark have said they are
willing to send troops to take part in the exercises.
</P>
<P>
The Central Asian Peacekeeping Camp, based in Kazakhstan, was
established in May 1996, with more than 500 servicemen from
Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
On March 11-13, NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana visited
the three Central Asian nations (Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan and
Uzbekistan) for talks with the three defense ministers on the
"Central Asian Peacekeeping Camp-97'" military exercises. 
