<HEADLINE> Indian Foreign Minister Wants to Have Exclusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Indian External Affairs
Minister I.K. Gujral is seeking to have exclusive talks with his
Pakistani counterpart Gohar Ayub Khan early next month, an
informed source said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the event of a positive response from Islamabad to Gujral's
proposal, conveyed Thursday in a letter to Gohar Ayub Khan, the
foreign ministers of the two countries would be setting up a
negotiating table in a little over a week after the March 28-31
foreign secretary-level talks scheduled in New Delhi, capital of
India.
</P>
<P>
There is no fixed agenda for the dialogue between the foreign
secretaries. But as suggested by Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif in a letter last month to the Indian prime minister, the
foreign secretary-level talks could prepare the ground for a
dialogue between the political leadership of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Originally, the two foreign ministers were to meet on the
fringes of the non-aligned movement (NAM) ministerial conference
scheduled here in the first week of April. In his letter to Gohar
Ayub, however, Gujral has invited him to stay on after the
conclusion of the NAM meeting for a regular bilateral talks. The
dates suggested by Gujral for the talks are April 8-9.
</P>
<P>
"Cooperative and friendly relations with our neighbors are in
the interest of South Asia. That's the essence of our policy which
applies equally to Pakistan," Gujral said here Thursday.  
</P>
