<HEADLINE> Italy Calls For NATO Role in Albanian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Italy said today there could be a
role for NATO in the Albania crisis and suggested the alliance
monitor and analyze the situation in the Balkan state.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Foreign Ministry proposed that North Atlantic
Treaty Organization consider such a monitoring role, and sketch
out contingency plans and examine the probable consequences.
</P>
<P>
The ministry pointed out that today's Albanian calls for
intervention by NATO or the West European Union did not come from
President Sali Berisha, as widely reported, but from the newly
formed government.
</P>
<P>
The point is important, the ministry said, because the interim
government is headed by an opposition leader, Bashkim Fino.
</P>
<P>
It said Rome had mounted pressure in recent days to broaden the
government to include all political forces.
</P>
<P>
In the present situation, with much of the population armed,
not all the forces are capable of dialogue, said Rome.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Italy and the international community urged
forces to return to the path of dialogue, lay down arms and
prepare for elections at the beginning of June.
</P>
<P>
Rome stressed that even faced with an extremely difficult
situation, diplomatic efforts were being made.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini discussed with his European
Union colleague, Hans van Mierlo, the way to facilitate the
immediate delivery of humanitarian and financial aid to help
restore order in the country.
</P>
<P>
Dini consulted former Austrian chancellor Franz Vranitzsky, who
is heading for Tirana on an Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe mission. He also spoke by phone to the new
Albanian prime minister and discussed national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Albania was plunged into unrest two weeks ago in the wake of
the collapse of dozens of pyramid savings schemes in which
hundreds of thousands of Albanians were left penniless.
</P>
<P>
President Berisha was blamed for allowing the schemes, and
the people demanded he resign.
</P>
<P>
He was forced on Sunday to change his hardline position and
agree to form an all-party interim government to stem the unrest
and oversee early elections in June.
</P>
<P>
Despite the formation of the interim government, unrest still
plagues the country. Hundreds of thousands of automatic weapons
are believed in the hands of the civilians and the government
has lost control in most of the south.
</P>
<P>
About 40 people have been killed in clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
