<HEADLINE> Italian Trade Surplus Hits Six-year High in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Italy's trade surplus rose 48
percent last year to a six-year record of 67,483 billion liras
(42.17 billion U.S. dollars), according to the national statistics
agency, ISTAT.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures released today by ISTAT show that the trade
surplus in 1996 was 21,969 billion liras (about 13.72 billion
dollars) up compared with the 45,514 billion liras (28.45 billion
dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The agency attributed the rise in the surplus to a 4.9 percent
fall in imports and 1.8 percent growth in exports in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Italy had an overall trade surplus of 19,429 billion liras
(12.14 billion dollars) last year with the European Union,
despite having a deficit with a few member countries. Its trade
surplus with non EU countries was 48,054 billion liras (30 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
ISTAT said that sectors showing a trade surplus were
machinery, processed products, textile, feather goods, clothing,
transportation tools, metal and non-metal commodities.
</P>
<P>
But there were deficits in ferrous and non-ferrous metals,
energy, chemical products, food, beverages, tobacco, agricultural
and fishery goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
