<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Usury Goes Wild in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Three years ago, the owner of a
dress shop in Italy borrowed five million Italian liras (2,950
U.S. dollars) from a priest.
</P>
<P>
But now she faces a repayment bill which has swollen to 80
million liras(47,200 dollars). If she doesn't pay up, her store
is likely to be destroyed by Mafia.
</P>
<P>
The shopowner is one of more than 500,000 people who are in
debts to usurers, or loan sharks, in Italy in a parallel credit
market estimated at 46,000 billion liras (27.14 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Grim statistics were released today in a report by the Italian
traders' association Confesercenti about the rising tide of usury
affecting more than 120,000 businessmen and 340,000 private
individuals.
</P>
<P>
Each year scores of Italians commit suicide to escape the
clutches of loan sharks and thousands of small businesses are
adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
Italy has now started to face the problem and try and curb
it. Last March parliament passed a draft law considering any
interest rate 50 percent higher than the national average lending
rate to be usurious.
</P>
<P>
And loan sharks face between one and six years in prison and
fines of up to 30 million liras (18,750 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
But mob-controlled usury is still a headache for Rome and some
bank officials have joined the outlawed trade, compounding an
already serious problem. Over the past three years, police have
found that about 65,650 billion liras (38.73 billion dollars) of
usurious loans were made by bankers.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been a steep drop in complaints to police
despite the growing number of victims of loan sharks, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Between 1994 and 1996, an average of less than 2,000 people a
year have gone on trial for usury. Last year, there were only 370
arrests in connection with usury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 20 Killed in Blast in Southern India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Over 20 people were killed and
50 others injured in a powerful blast in a godown in southern
India's Maharashtra state Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that the explosion destroyed
about 50 houses situated within 100 meters of the ravaged godown.
Most of the victims were farm laborers in the vicinity and some
passers-by. 19 bodies, mutilated beyond recognition, including
seven women and two children, were recovered by police late
Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
A small truck and a jeep standing outside the godown were
completely smashed. At least eight other vehicles were also
damaged.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses reported two successive blasts inside the godown,
first a minor one which possibly triggered the second major blast.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations have ruled out the possibility of a
sabotage. A mistake in handling the gelatin sticks might have
caused the blast, Satara district collector Vandana Khuller said.
</P>
<P>
A bomb disposal squad as well as fire tenders and ambulances
were rushed to the spot. The police have summoned explosive
experts and the debris would be cleared after consulting them,
police said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
