<HEADLINE> U.S. Lockheed to Make Satellite for Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's state-owned domestic
telecommunications firm Pt. Telkom has chosen US company Lockheed
Marin Corp. to build its 36-transponder satellite which will be
launched by late 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Negotiations between Telkom's elite and Lockheed executives
are still in progress," local press today quoted Telkom executive
Harso as saying here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Telkom, the contract is worth 140 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The new satellite, Telkom 1, will replace the 24-transponder
Palapa b-2r satellite.
</P>
<P>
Telkom 1 will have a 15-year lifespan and be lighter than
Indonesia's current Palapa b satellites, which have a eight year
lifespan.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has operated three generations of Palapa satellite
since 1970 to support its vast communication areas as well as
countries in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
At present, Indonesia owns 18 major ground stations, 19 medium
and 84 minor ground stations linking the country's 27 provinces
and 18 other sites in the Asia-Pacific region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
