<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Should Consider Russia's Interests on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russia and the West can find a way
to solve their dispute over NATO's eastward expansion if the West
puts Russia's interests on an equal footing with its own, the
Russian Defence Council said here today.
</P>
<P>
The council, made up of the heads of Russian "power
ministries", such as Defense and the Interior were meeting to
prepare for next week's Russian-U.S. summit in Helsinki between
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Top of the agenda were issues relating to NATO's proposal to
let members of the former Warsaw Pact join its military alliance.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, who chaired the meeting,
said Russia still held the opinion that there would be no real
security in Europe without Russia.
</P>
<P>
If NATO carries out its eastward expansion without considering
Russia's interests, "the whole Europe will have a difficult time
ahead," said Chernomyrdin.
</P>
<P>
Several former Warsaw Pact nations have been bidding to join
NATO for security reasons since the beginning of 1990s. The United
States and its NATO allies will meet in Madrid in July to decide
which countries will be first to be invited to join the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Defense Council Secretary Yuri Batruin echoed the prime
minister's view.
</P>
<P>
He told Interfax news agency that relations between Russia and
the West, security in Europe and the future of Russia's reform
will mainly depend on the easing of tensions which have arisen
from NATO enlargement and the guarantee of a partnership role for
Russia in the new international order.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Council, which is headed by President Boris Yeltsin
and Chernomyrdin, is a permanent consultative institution for the
country's military matters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
