<HEADLINE> New Thai Satellite to Be Launched in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The European satellite launcher
Arianespace will launch a new satellite for Thailand on April 12,
the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The launch of Thaicom 3 scheduled for 6 a.m. (Thailand time)
from Arianespace's facility at Kourou in French Guyana has been
confirmed by the launcher.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, the third one of Thailand, will be delivered
into orbit at 78.5 degrees east to replace Thaicom 1, which will
be shifted to a position at 120 degrees east.
</P>
<P>
Thaicom 3 will be mainly used for broadcasting, while Thaicom 1
will be used for telecommunication signaling.
</P>
<P>
The transfer will not affect clients because they need not to
change their satellite dishes, according to Shinawatra Satellite
PLC (SSA), a Thai satellite operator.
</P>
<P>
The company's next satellite, Thaicom 4 which was built
simultaneously with Thaicom 3 to serve as a backup, is scheduled
to be launched early next year.
</P>
<P>
If a problem occurs with Thaicom 3, Thaicom 4 could be launched
within six months, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Dumrong Kasemset, chairman of the SSA, said that Thaicom 3 will
help change the company's status from a domestic satellite
operator to a regional operator.
</P>
<P>
Only 10 percent of the customers for the previous two Thai
satellites are foreigners, while about half of Thaicom 3 's
customers are from outside Thailand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
