<HEADLINE> Dollar Rebounds on Signs of U.S. Economic Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar surged Thursday
with new indications of a healthy United States economy -- which
might result in interest rate hikes by the Federal Reserve later
this month.
</P>
<P>
However, the message, seen as a signal of inflation, evoked a
plunge in the U.S. stock and bond markets, with the Dow Jones
industrial average falling 160.48 points, its fifth worst point
decline.
</P>
<P>
The dollar against German marks settled in New York at 1.7056
marks, up from 1.6932 Wednesday. Against the yen, the dollar
closed at its highest level since February 19, at 123.41 yen, up
from 122.34 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The pound traded 1.5974 U.S. dollars, down from 1.5992 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rise of the dollar followed a decline Wednesday, triggered
by the latest report of the Fed' revealing a moderate growth of
the economy, which suggested the Fed' would not raise interest
rates soon.
</P>
<P>
However, the Commerce Department today reported a sharp rise in
February retail sales and a higher revised figure for January. The
Labor Department also reported reducing jobless claims instead of
an expected mild increase in unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late
Wednesday: 1.4657 Swiss francs, up from 1.4552; 5.7520 French
francs, up from 5.7100; 1,697.00 Italian lire, up from 1,687.50;
1.3650 Canadian dollars, up from 1.3627. 
</P>
</TEXT>
