<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Names New Chief for Military Space Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today named Valeri Grin as the new commander for Russia's Military
Space Forces.
</P>
<P>
Grin, 60, has been an acting commander for the space forces
ever since October 1996, when Gen. Vladimir Ivanov was dismissed
from the position at the start of Yeltsin's military reforms to
restore combat effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
Grin, who has been working for Russia space industry for over
21 years, said that his major task as commander would be to
protect Russia's space potential, and develop new carrier rockets
and spacecrafts in line with the country's financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin ordered Chernomyrdin to reorganise his government after
his annual state-of-the-nation speech on Thursday in which he
attacked its failure to tackle Russia's economic and social
problems, including chronic delays in the payment of wages and
pensions.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Chernomyrdin, a trusted Yeltsin ally who epitomises
Russian reforms to the outside world, the only man guaranteed to
keep his job is the newly appointed First Deputy Prime Minister
Anatoly Chubais.
</P>
<P>
Interfax news agency, quoting "well-informed sources", said the
heads of most "power ministries" -- defense and interior
ministries and security organs that answer directly to Yeltsin --
were unlikely to be changed, probably with the exception of
defense Minister Igor Rodionov.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said on Wednesday his new cabinet, which he has
promised to present by the end of the week, would be younger and
more professional and include market-minded reformers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
