<HEADLINE> Albania Calls for Military Help From Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Albanian President Sali Berisha
and all political parties have called on the Western European
Union to provide military assistance to Tirana to restore order in
the Balkan country which is on the verge of civil war.
</P>
<P>
The appeal issued here yesterday said outside military
assistance was needed "to restore constitutional order and
maintain the country's integrity."
</P>
<P>
The appeal to the European Union's fledgling defence arm came
only hours after a new Albanian government was sworn in to take
charge of the country until early elections are held in June.
</P>
<P>
Albania has been in the grip of unrest since January after the
collapse of pyramid investment schemes in which thousands of
Albanians lost their life savings.
</P>
<P>
The protests turned violent two weeks ago as rebels looted
weapons from army depots and startged fighting the
military. Several cities in southern Albania are in the hands of
rebels who are now threatening to move onto the capital.
</P>
<P>
The international airport just outside Tirana was closed today
after a nearby military base was looted.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, the Western European Union said it had received no
request from Albania to provide military assistance. 
</P>
