<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Decides Not to Sign Turtle-Protection Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations has decided not to sign an agreement with the United
States to protect sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made Thursday at a two-day meeting on ASEAN
fisheries at northern Thailand's Chiang Rai province, a report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN representatives agreed that ASEAN nations should
continue to conserve the turtles without signing the treaty,
Plodprasop Suraswadi, director-general of the Fisheries Department
of the Thai government was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said entering into an agreement with the United States made
no difference as ASEAN countries had long run programs to save the
sea turtles and were soon to sign their own pact on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The representatives also asked Thailand to work on helping
develop ASEAN's shrimp farming industry and to counter the
criticism of foreign non-government organizations which accused
the industry of threatening turtle habitats.
</P>
<P>
Last May, the US Court of International Trade imposed a ban on
shrimp imports from Thailand and 51 other countries. It said they
caught shrimps without taking steps to protect endangered turtles.
</P>
<P>
However, Thailand was later removed from the US list after
proving its shrimp vessels were equipped with turtle excluding
devices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
