<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin: NATO Expansion Hard for Whole Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin on Thursday repeated Moscow's opposition to NATO's
planned eastward enlargement, warning it could bring difficult
times for the whole of Europe.
</P>
<P>
Chairing a meeting of the Russian Defense Council held on the
orders of President Boris Yeltsin, the premier said, "today we
must detail the tactics of negotiating with NATO and weigh up the
proposals which have emerged recently."
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said Russia's negative stance over such plans was
clearly outlined in the president's message to the Federal
Assembly earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, its future policy depends on the outcome of
the Helsinki summit between the presidents of Russia and the
United States on March 20.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin will make an official visit to Washington on March
15 and is expected to meet with U.S. President Bill Clinton and US
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The two sides intend to focus on problems of European security
and a package of agreements on strategic arms limitation and
anti-missile defense, according to Russian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Gennady Tarasov.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov told a briefing here Thursday the same themes will be
discussed at the forthcoming summit between Boris Yeltsin and Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
NATO's eastward expansion was described Wednesday by Yeltsin's
press secretary Sergei Yastrzhembsky as "the most serious
strategic mistake the West has ever made in the detente period".
</P>
<P>
Sergei said in an interview with a Moscow radio station that
Russian President Boris Yeltsin will point out this mistake when
he meets Bill Clinton in Helsinki. 
</P>
