<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uzbeks Not Worried by NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TASHKENT, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Uzbek President Islam Karimov
said today that he does not view the eastward expansion of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) as a threat to
Uzbekistan and the Central Asian region.
</P>
<P>
He hoped NATO and Russia would reach an agreement on the issue
quickly.
</P>
<P>
Karimov made the remarks when meeting visiting
Secretary-General of NATO, Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
He said that as a member nation of NATO's "partnership for
peace" plan, Uzbekistan has established good cooperative relations
with NATO.
</P>
<P>
Countries applying for NATO membership had made the decision in
consideration of their national interests and Uzbekistan
understood their will and respected their choice.
</P>
<P>
Solana, who is on his first visit to Uzbekistan, briefed
Karimov on NATO's present situation and its plan for future
development, including the eastward enlargement. He said his visit
would help further strengthen cooperation between Uzbekistan and
NATO.
</P>
<P>
He said that NATO viewed Uzbekistan as the most important
partner in Central Asia and the two sides should maintain friendly
cooperation, to guarantee peace, stability and security in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Karimov said that as a member of the Organization for Security
and Cooperation in Europe, his country would make contributions to
the regional security as well as world peace through establishing
a new type of cooperation with NATO.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Solana also held talks with Uzbek Foreign
Minister Abdulaziz Kamilov and Defense Minister Rustam Akhmedov,
on the situation in Central Asia and cooperation between
Uzbekistan and NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
