<HEADLINE> "Rio Plus Five" Forum Opens in Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- More than 500
environmental experts from 80 countries gathered here today for
the International Conference on the Environment and
Sustainable Development.
</P>
<P>
The forum, also known as "Rio Plus Five", following the Earth
Summit in Rio De Janeiro in 1992, is organized by the
Committee of the Brazilian Forum of Non-Governmental Organizations
and Social Movements for the Environment and Development.
</P>
<P>
The week-long conference aims to review and promote the
sustainable development plan set up by the "Agenda 21" adopted
by the 1992 United Nations summit, and make recommendations for
the meeting of the U.N. Sustainable Development Commission in
April in New York.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to draft a document called "Letter from Earth,"
which has been in discussion since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The delegates will review more than 70 documents related to
sustainable development, including commitments to controlling
pollution and protecting biological diversity. 
</P>
