<HEADLINE> Chang Stays On Course For Indian Wells Repeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion Michael
Chang stayed on course for a tournament title repeat on Thursday
with a straight-set victory over Marc Rosset in the third round
of the ATP Tour Tournament played at Indian Wells, California.
</P>
<P>
Chang, seeded third, got rid of the big-serving Swiss 6-2, 7-5
and advanced to a quarter-final battle with France's Cedric
Pioline.
</P>
<P>
Pioline, trying to turn around a year that has so far proved
unfortunate, downed Swedish wild card Magnus Larsson 6-7 (6-8),
6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Second seed Thomas Muster, the highest seed left in the draw,
won his way 6-4, 6-4 into the quarter-finals at the Czech Slava
Dosedel's expense.
</P>
<P>
With world number-one Pete Sampras, fourth seed Goran
Ivanisevic, number five Marcelo Rios and number six Thomas
Enqvist already out, talk was turning on Thursday to a possible
semi-final showdown between Muster and Chang.
</P>
<P>
But Muster has to get there by passing the 20-year-old
Australian Mark Philippoussis in the first place, who upset
eighth-seeded Spaniard Carlos Moya 6-4, 6-3 to reach the last
eight.
</P>
<P>
Philippoussis, who won his first ATP Tour title in Scottsdale,
Arizona, last Sunday, stretched his winning run to eight matches
with the victory over the Australian Open finalist.
</P>
<P>
The top half of the draw was looking considerably more open,
with Spain's Alberto Berasategui the only seeded player left.
</P>
<P>
The number 14 defeated American wild card Jonathan Stark 7-6
(8-6), 6-3 to set up a quarter-final clash with Sweden's Jonas
Bjorkman. Bjorkman beat American Chris Woodruff 2-6, 7-5, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Czech Bohdan Ulihrach, who bumped out Pete Sampras in the
second round on Wednesday, qualified with a 7-5, 7-6 (7-5)
victory over Spain's Francisco Clavet.
</P>
<P>
Ulihrach will face Zimbabwe's Byron Black in the round of
eight. Black ousted Brazilian qualifier Gustavo Kuerten 6-3,
6-3. 
</P>
