<HEADLINE> Soeharto Renews Warning to Election Boycotters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
warned again that people who incited others to boycott the
elections would be punished.
</P>
<P>
Every citizen is free to vote or not vote but no one may
prevent others from exercising their right, Soeharto said Thursday
during a visit to Sigli in eastern Indonesia, reports reaching
here today said.
</P>
<P>
The president's comments came amid reports of anonymous
campaigns encouraging people to boycott the upcoming general
elections scheduled on May 29 this year.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Golkar, the United Development Party (PPP) and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) will contest 425 of the 500
seats in the house of representatives in the elections. The
remaining 75 seats will be allocated to the armed forces, whose
members do not vote.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto said he had learned some people were not going to the
polls and were trying to persuade others to do the same.
</P>
<P>
Security authorities in various provinces have reported seizing
anonymous leaflets that urged people to boycott the elections.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Democratic Union party has openly called for a
boycott. Its chairman Sri Bintang Pamungkas and another two
activities have been detained and charged with subversion.
</P>
<P>
The government has set up alert centers across the country to
deal with security disturbances.
</P>
<P>
About 125 million people have been registered as voters in the
general elections.
</P>
<P>
The general elections will be followed by the presidential
elections in March, 1998, in the people's consultative assembly.
Many observers believe Soeharto will be re-elected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
