<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador's Economic Growth Slows in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's economic growth rate
slowed to 1.5 percent in 1996, less than half the 3.2 percent rate
registered in 1995, according to the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector, which represented 15.2 percent of the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP), showed a sluggish growth of 0.8
percent in 1996, down from 3.1 percent the previous year.
Agriculture also diminished from 3.1 percent to 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The slower pace was attributed to the contraction and poor
performance of the oil sector last year, which accounted for 13.7
percent of the GDP, the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
Best sector performer in 1996 was electricity, which reversed a
1.6 percent contraction in 1995 and grew 4.2 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
Construction was also reactivated, moving from a 0.3 percent
drop in 1995, to a 0.7 percent growth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Commerce improved, going from a 3.5 percent expansion to 4.6
percent. Transport grew from 2.5 percent to 2.6 percent between
the same periods of 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Other services, such as hotels, restaurants, communications,
housing, services to enterprises and homes, grew 4.2 percent in
1996, compared to 2.5 percent in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
