<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Susi Susanti, most probably, bid
farewell for good to the All England Championships, a tournament
she virtually made her own during the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The four times All England winner and ex-World and Olympic
champion went down to second seed Chinese Gong Zhichao 11-4, 11-7
in their quater-final clash on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the 26-year-old Susanti, only jointly seeded fifth in
this year's tournament and having her days at top international
level maybe numbered, said after Thursday's defeat that she still
wanted to go on for a couple of years given fitness permission.
</P>
<P>
Susanti, getting married last month with her long time
sweetheart Allan Budi Kusuma, first won the All England title in
1990 and followed up with further success in 1991, 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
But on Thursday she only found no match for the 19-year-old
Gong, who has advanced into Friday's semifinal match against
unseeded Ra Kyung-min. The South Korean upset joint third seed
Camilla Martin of Denmark in a 62-minute tussle 11-7, 11-12, 11-6.
</P>
<P>
The other semifinal will be between China's world champion Ye
Zhaoying and unseeded compatriot Dai Yun, the woman who on
Wednesday eliminated top seed Mia Audina of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, world champion and former All England
title holder Heryanto Arbi reached the semifinals with a three-set
victory over unseeded Chinese Luo Yigang.
</P>
<P>
A final against Olympic champion Poul-Erik Hoyer Larsen on
Saturday was looking on the cards.
</P>
<P>
There was something for the locals to cheer when English
couple Chris Hunt and Donna Kellogg reached the semifinals of the
mixed doubles, beating the joint fifth seeds from Russia Nickoial
Zuev and Marina Yakusheva in straight games. 
</P>
