<HEADLINE> Manila Extends Ban on Sugar Imports to July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Sugar Regulatory Administration
chief Wilson Gamboa has ordered an extension of the Philippines'
ban on sugar imports to July this year.
</P>
<P>
Today's local press reported that the order was issued to
ensure the large stocks of sugar in the country's warehouses were
exhausted. The stocks were estimated at 100,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to extend the sugar importation ban to July,
at which time we expect the glut to have eased," Gamboa said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic sugar glut was due to the importation of 1.02
million tons of sugar from neighboring countries in crop year
1995-1996 against production shortfalls of 500,000 tons. The large
imports volume led to a sharp fall in the sugar prices.
</P>
<P>
To ease the glut, Gamboa asked traders and millers in the
country last October to stop sugar imports up to March this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
