<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Have Negative Population Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the country's largest
municipal in East China, is expected to maintain a negative
population growth for many years, reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yongliang, deputy director of the Shanghai Municipal
Family Planning Commission said family planning in Shanghai has
advanced to a new level that emphasizes reproductive health
education at a grass-roots level and services for the large number
of laid-off workers and the more than 3.5 million floating
population.
</P>
<P>
With a birth rate of 5.6 thousand last year which is 11 per
thousand lower than the national average, Shanghai has experienced
a negative population growth for the past six years, starting
first in six of its 14 urban districts in 1991, and then,
beginning in 1993, in the whole municipality.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the natural population growth in the
municipality stablized at an annual rate of about minus one per
thousand. Shanghai has a registered permanent population of 13.09
million.
</P>
<P>
Liu attributed the low birth rate to the implementation of
various family planning educational activities and services.
Rapid economic development and expanded international exchanges
also helped reform the public's idea about reproduction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai adopted a policy of "one couple, one child" in 1979.
In the years following, increasing numbers of residents began to
think less about wanting more children and more about having a
healthy child.
</P>
<P>
A survey among some 2,000 Shanghai residents who are in their
reproductive years suggested 94 percent were eager to learn about
pre-natal care, safe child-birth procedures and good child-rearing
practices.
</P>
<P>
Prevention of hereditary diseases, scientific measures for
bringing up children, marriage and healthy birth were identified
as the main concerns for most people. Some 88 percent of those
surveyed asked for sex and health education.
</P>
<P>
Liu said that the municipal government is revising the city's
regulations on family planning work this year to further clarify
activities regarding reproductive health education and services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Department Stores Join Hands to Improve Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A total of 50 department stores
in some 40 major Chinese cities have promised to provide joint
services, allowing buyers to have commodities repaired or replace
them at any participating store.
</P>
<P>
The new services, aiming to improve service quality of
state-owned retail sellers, have been available at the stores on a
voluntary basis Thursday, according to a report in today's "China
Daily."
</P>
<P>
The services allow customers who buy commodities at any one of
the participating stores to go for repairs or replacements to any
store either in the same city or in a different one, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
All that is necessary is that the customer should go to a store
within 30 days of the purchase with the sales receipt, the report
quoted Xia Gengxue, an official with the Ministry of Internal
Trade, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Items that may not be replaced include food, underwear,
personal sanitary items, photo-sensitive materials, gold and
silver ornaments, discounted items and other goods that can not be
replaced according to law, she said.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of the national drive to curb the flow of sham
products into the markets, especially state-owned markets, improve
business and management and make it easier for consumers to return
or replace unsatisfactory buys," she said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has set up a special office in charge of the joint
services. "Any fake products found in any of the stores must be
reported to the office, and the office will inform other
joint-service stores to be on the watch for similar fake goods,"
the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
