<HEADLINE> Shanghai Farmers' Paintings Enter Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A collection of "farmer's art"
painted by local artists in Jinshan County, Shanghai, has been
logged onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The Jinshan farmers' paintings, which are unique for their
primitive, vibrantly-colored depiction of country life, have been
exhibited in over a dozen countries including the United States,
Japan, France, Germany, Singapore and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
There are over 300 farmers-turned painters in Jinshan. Many
overseas tourists have visited the county's Farmers' Art Institute
to buy the works; over 4,000 of the paintings are sold abroad
every year.
</P>
<P>
The county has been named the "Home of Modern Chinese
Paintings" by the Ministry of Culture.
</P>
<P>
Jinshan recently cooperated with a Canadian computer company to
enter over 600 farmers' paintings onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
A large number of orders have come from foreign countries and
regions, according to Zhou Jianqing, director of the
institute. "More and more people will get to know the farmers'
paintings in Jinshan and there will be more fans and buyers," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
