<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Concerned Over Food Delay in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 13 (Xinhua) --The Security Council today
expressed concern over the slow pace of food and medical
deliveries to Iraq under the United Nation's "oil-for-food" plan.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council, while welcoming the smooth operation
concerning Iraqi oil, expresses concern regarding the humanitarian
aspect of the implementation of resolution 986," council president
Zbigniew Wlosowicz of Poland told the press.
</P>
<P>
Under Security Council Resolution 986, Iraq was allowed to sell
up to two billion U.S. dollars worth of oil. It was to be in
exchange for food and medicine to alleviate the suffering of Iraqi
people caused by the U.N. sanctions imposed since 1990.
</P>
<P>
The plan was started on December 10, but after more than three
months no food and medicine have yet arrived in Iraq. Iraq has
blamed the United States and United Nations for the delay.
</P>
<P>
Wlosowicz said the Security Council wished for prompt delivery.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council has expressed the hope that, with further
efforts, humanitarian goods will be delivered to Iraq and
distributed on an equitable basis to all segments of Iraqi people
as soon as possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Security Council recognized that the implementation
of Resolution 986 was a complex and complicated operation, but
member states were committed to the purpose of the resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0299 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
