<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 14 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- More Australians are unemployed than at any time in the past
two and a half years, with the number forced to depend on a dole
payment climbing to almost 900,000. The jobless figure rose to 8.8
percent in February after holding at 8.6 percent over the previous
two months.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard yesterday pledged "faster and
stronger" economic growth after the Federal Government's
employment strategy was rocked by surging unemployment and a
downturn in full-time employment.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Victoria State's industrial climate may worsen, with health
unions foreshadowing a showdown with the State Government over
claims for a 15 percent wage rise, unions representing more than
20,000 public sector health workers are close to forming a united
front to pursue their wage claim.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australia has called for a new 1.5 trillion Australian
dollars (1.2 trillion US dollars) zone of economic co-operation
involving 14 countries on the rim of the Indian Ocean to adopt the
same ambitious tariff reduction targets as the APEC (Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation) forum.


