<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguayan Imports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Uruguayan imports reached
3.323 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, a big increase against
2.867 billion dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Information provided by the Central Bank shows that consumer
goods purchased abroad cost 866 million dollars at the end of
1996, amounting to 26 percent of total imports.
</P>
<P>
Purchases of machinery and transportation equipment also rose,
accounting for 24.9 percent and 32.5 percent of import values
respectively.
</P>
<P>
About 44 percent of Uruguayan purchases abroad came from its
South Common Market (Mercosur) partners, 22 percent from Europe,
12 percent from the United States, and 9.1 percent from Asian
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
