<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schifferer Wins Race, Alphand Captures Super-G Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Andreas Schifferer
won the World Cup Finals Super-G of the Alpine skiing and France's
Luc Alphand captured the season title at Vail, Colorado today.
</P>
<P>
Schifferer, who took world championship bronze in the giant
slalom at Sestriere, scored his first career World Cup victory
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Schifferer squeezed ahead of another Austrian,
Josef Strobl, by finishing in one minute, 33.76 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Kristian Ghedina of Italy finished third in 1:33.88, .041 of a
second ahead of compatriot Luca Cattaneo.
</P>
<P>
Alphand won the tittle with 351 points, while Strobl settled
for second place, 18 points behind. Schifferer surged into third
in the final standings ahead of compatriot Hermann Maier.
</P>
<P>
Alphand, who earlier this season clinched his third successive
downhill title, completed his sweep of the speed events but saw
his lead in the overall standings dwindle.
</P>
<P>
Andre Kjetil Aamodt of Norway, the 1994 overall winner,
finished fifth to draw closer in his challenge to Alphand. He
made up 16 points to trail Alphand by 106.
</P>
<P>
Aamodt, however, has two more races to run -- Saturday's giant
slalom and Sunday's slalom.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970314.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-03-14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First School Donated by Overseas Students Inaugurates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, March 14 (Xinhua) -- A primary school financed by
Chinese students studying in Japan recently opened in central
China's Henan Province.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the province said that the newly-built school is
the first of its kind in the country, which is funded by donations
from overseas Chinese students for "Project Hope," a nationwide
charity drive.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of such a school is aimed at boosting Chinese
education, said the donors, who collected funds of 4.7 million
Japanese yen within a few months.
</P>
<P>
The move also called on students studying abroad to contribute
more to the country's economic development and social progress,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
There are now more than 20,000 Chinese students studying in
Japan. In 1897, there were only 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
