<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seizinger Wins Race, Gerg Captures Super-G Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Katja Seizinger won
the last Super-G of the season while her compatriot Hilde Gerg
captured the women's season title at the World Cup Alpine skiing
Finals at Vail, Colorado on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 24-year-old Seizinger, who finished second in Wednesday's
downhill, won her 27th World Cup race with a time of one minute,
15.73 seconds, slicing through a tricky, 34-gate course.
</P>
<P>
Gerg followed Seizinger down the course and finished second in
1:16.53. Her second-place time was enough to push her past
Seizinger for the Super-G title.
</P>
<P>
Martina Ertl, another German, claimed third in 1:17.01,
six-hundredths of a second ahead of Ingeborg Helen Marken of
Norway.
</P>
<P>
Overall World Cup champion Pernilla Wiberg of Sweden entered
the race with a 39-point lead in the Super-G standings. But
Wiberg, who won her first career downhill here Wednesday, skied
out on the same blind turn that claimed Swiss star Heidi
Zurbriggen and Italian Isolde Kostner.
</P>
<P>
Gerg finished the season with 490 points, 16 better than
Seizinger. Wiberg settled for third with 449. 
</P>
</TEXT>
