<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks on Wall Street Plunge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Stocks tumbled on Wall Street
today, dragging the Dow Jones industrial average toward its fourth
biggest point drop ever, as inflation fears sent interest rates
higher.
</P>
<P>
At the closing, Dow lost 160.48 points, or 2.28 percent, to
6,878.89, led by a steep selloff in Philip Morris.
</P>
<P>
Most stocks were pressured at the beginning by the bond market,
where interest rates shot up amid news of surprisingly robust
retail sales during January and February.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume totaled 503.74 million
shares, more than 483.22 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 14.70, or 1.8
percent, to 789.56; the NYSE composite index fell 7.67 to 415.87,
and the American Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.02 to
598.02.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell just 10.86 to 1,293.27,
cushioned by a partial rebound in some technology issues beaten
down by recent profit-taking.
</P>
<P>
The active retail sales report compounded growing fears that
the Federal Reserve will soon raise interest rates to slow
economic activities as measures to control inflation.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell today, the yield on the 30-year Treasury
bond jumped as high as 6.98 percent, up from late Wednesday's 6.88
percent. The long-bond yield hasn't been above 7 percent since
September.
</P>
<P>
The Commerce Department reported this morning that retail sales
rose 0.8 percent in February, slightly higher than expected. Last
month's initial estimate of January's increase, meanwhile, was
revised sharply from 0.6 percent to 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the Labor Department said new claims for
jobless benefits fell by 5,000 last week to the lowest level in
more than two years, reflecting a tightening labor market that
could force wages and consumer prices higher.
</P>
<P>
Overseas, Tokyo's Nikkei stock average fell 1.6 percent,
Frankfurt's DAX index fell 1.9 percent, and London's FT-SE 100 fell
0.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
