<HEADLINE> Chinese Naval Ships Leave Pearl Harbor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONOLULU, March 13 (Xinhua) --Three Chinese naval ships,
winding up a four-day visit here, left Pearl Harbor this morning.
</P>
<P>
Their next stop is San Diago, the first mainland U.S. port city
in southern California to be visited by Chinese naval vessels.
</P>
<P>
Made up of two missile guided destroyers and an oiler, the
group arrived at the harbor March 9. In the following days, when
admirals from both navies held meetings, the Chinese and American
sailors had picnics together, made reciprocal ship visits,
attended a concert and held sports competitions.
</P>
<P>
Two speakers at the departure ceremony for the leaving ships
and some 800 sailors under the command of Vice Admiral Wang
Yongguo described the visit a great success.
</P>
<P>
Rear Admiral William G. Sutton, commander of the Pearl Harbor
Naval Base, highlighted sailor-to-sailor exchange on the ships,
which he said crossed the lines of culture and languages. He
praised the Chinese sailors for their professionalism and devotion
to work, which he said have won the respect of their American
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Rear Admiral Li Xiukang, head of the political department of
the Chinese navy South China Sea fleet, said that extensive
contacts between officers and sailors of the two navies have
promoted, mutual understanding and increased bilateral friendship.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua on another occasion, Admiral
Archie Clemins, commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific fleet,
described the visit by the Chinese naval ships as a first step
toward close cooperation between the two navies. He expected a
visit to China by one or two ships from the Seventh Fleet later
this year.
</P>
<P>
Clemins said that the Chinese ships were well kept and operated
and that he was impressed by the Chinese sailors' good behavior
and professionalism.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ships weighed anchor at eight o'clock and are due
to arrive in San Diego March 21. They will also tour Mexico, Peru
and Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
