<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Starts Evacuation from Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The United States today began
evacuating Americans from Albania with U.S. military aircraft,
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns announced.
</P>
<P>
Four Chinook 46 helicopters landed earlier today at Tirana from
the U.S. fleet in the Ionian Sea and evacuated the first 50
Americans. At least 170 were due to follow, Burns told a news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"Because the situation in Albania has taken such a dramatic
turn for the worse over the last 24 hours... the United States has
decided to bring out all of our citizens and non-essential
government employees by United States military aircraft," Burns
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. military will continue the evacuation in the
next few days, bringing out all those who wish to be brought out.
There are about 2,000 American civilians living in Albania.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. will still keep some 17 State Department
officials, including Ambassador Marisa Lino, in the Embassy in
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Burns said that a North Atlantic Council meeting is
under way in Brussels to discuss the evacuation by military means
from Albania. Italy has reportedly begun evacuating its citizens.
</P>
<P>
"So we'd like to make this a coordinated evacuation of
foreigners, civilians from Albania, over the course of the next
couple of hours," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had hoped to evacuate its citizens by commercial
flights, but the airport in Tirana was shut down Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the U.S. would help to keep the conflict in Albania
from spilling over to its neighboring countries, Burns said, "We
have to take first things first."
</P>
<P>
"The first obligation of the United States government is to
protect American government employees and American civilians and
to bring them out," he affirmed.
</P>
<P>
"As of today, we see no indications that the conflict in
Albania is going to spill over into Macedonia or into other
countries, Greece or Italy, other countries that neighbor
Albania," he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) do not plan to intervene in the conflict. "I
don't believe any formal planning is under way for that."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
