<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Anti-Corruption Leaders to Declare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 13 (Xinhua) -- All senior officials in
the Anti-Corruption Bureau of Tanzania have resolved to declare
their property in response to President Benjamin Mkapa's
directive to public institutions to clean their ranks.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Kamasima, the bureau's General Director, said here
today the resolution was adopted at the end of a seminar held in
the town of Bagamoyo, about 70 kilometers north of here on
February 21-22.
</P>
<P>
Kamasima said officials who are required to declare their
wealth under the resolution include heads of department and zonal
directors.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the officials' reports could be ready by
mid-April.
</P>
<P>
He asked the general public to offer any relevant information
they might have to the bureau's head office here or at various
districts or to the regional commissioners' offices.
</P>
<P>
"If the public knows any bureau employee or leader who is
corrupt or has property believed to have been corruptly acquired,
they should give us the names," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa has urged public leaders to declare their property as a
part of the government's strategy to get an open and transparent
public service.
</P>
<P>
Public institutions have also been directed to submit their
action reports to the prime minister's office in an attempt to curb
the practice in their respective bodies before the end of next
June. enditem

