<HEADLINE> Killing of Israeli Schoolgirls Shocks U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said today that he was shocked by the killing of seven
Israeli schoolgirls and he called on to quicken the peace process
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued here this afternoon by the spokesman for the
U.N. head said that the secretary-general was shocked by the news
that a Jordanian soldier fired upon a group of Israeli
schoolgirls, killing seven and wounding several others.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general deplored this act of violence, and
extended condolences to the families of the victims and the
government and people of Israel, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
"Today's tragic incident highlights the need to renew
confidence in the peace process, whose objective is the
achievement of a comprehensive, just and lasting settlement in the
Middle East," Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said a Jordanian gunman fired into Israel on
Thursday, killing and wounding several people.
</P>
<P>
It said the shooting occurred near Naharayim in the Jordan
Valley. It also reported later that Jordan is investigating that
reports.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the General Assembly of the U.N. this
afternoon, representatives from different countries also expressed
their condolences to the Israeli families who lost their children
and called for speedy peace process in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
