<HEADLINE> Protests against National Front Intensify in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- Militants against the extreme-right
National Front (FN) party have intensified protests against the
party of Jean-Marie Le Pen, with two protests launched today in
Paris and the eastern city of Reims.
</P>
<P>
About 20 youths ransacked today the stand displaying books
written by FN leaders and supporters at the Paris Book Saloon, and
the regional councillor of FN Picardie Lionel was slightly injured
in clash with the protesters.
</P>
<P>
Clash took place this evening in Reims, eastern France, between
police and a group of youths who protested the visit paid by the
number two of FN Bruno Megret to the city.
</P>
<P>
Three people were arrested by police in the clash, during which
one policeman was slightly injured by a stone thrown by the
protesters, who also broke some shop windows, according to local
media reports.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes took place Tuesday night between police and
anti-FN demonstrators in Marseille, during a big protest rally held
by 5,000 demonstrators outside a meeting place where Le Pen and
Megret were making speeches.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested at least 10 people and used tear gas to disperse
the protesters, while a grenade was thrown at the FN office in
Marseille and caused some damages.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist mayor of Strasbourg Catherine Trautmann is planning
to mobilize the residents of the eastern French city to stage
protests when the FN holds its first national congress in the city
by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
A protest was staged earlier this week by thousands in Nice,
southern France, where Le Pen chaired a meeting of FN supporters to
present the nine candidates of FN for the 1998 legislative elections
in the southern department of Alpes-Maritimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
