<HEADLINE> Microsoft, Intel Release NetPC Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The world's two leading
computer companies, Microsoft and Intel, released the NetPC
reference standards Wednesday in Germany, the Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
Intel, the biggest maker of microprocessor chips, and
Microsoft, the No. 1 PC software maker, said they developed a set
of technical standards to help more than 100 of the world's top
computer manufacturers including Compaq, Dell and Hewlett-Packard,
build NetPCs.
</P>
<P>
"NetPC product announcements from many leading PC manufacturers
are expected over the next 90 days." Microsoft said.
</P>
<P>
Net PCs, including no floppy or CD-Rom drivers, will require
users to rely on remote computers for softwares. These features
may lower ownership and management costs while keeping the
performance and flexibility of traditional PCs.
</P>
<P>
The Microsoft-Intel NetPC features will include that all
hardware devices can be recognized and managed by software,
systems can be automatically configured and installed over the
network, and a sealed case prevents modifications by end users to
the hardware configuration.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the NetPC is a great business computer because it
delivers compatibility with today's standard PC and network
infrastructure with dramatically reduced management and support
costs, " said Jim Allchin, senior vice president of the personal
and business systems group at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Also, Microsoft "expects many of the innovative NetPC features
to find their way into other PC product lines," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
