<HEADLINE> King Hussein Expressed Deepest Sorrow on Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 13 (Xinhua) -- "I feel the way they (Israelis)
feel", said King of Jordan Hussein tonight upon his return from
Spain when talking about the shooting of Israeli students by a
Jordanian soldier earlier today.
</P>
<P>
Hussein cut short his visit to Spain and came back to Amman
tonight to settle the issue.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference he held at the airport, the King called
the incident as "very violent crime, inhuman and totally
unacceptable".
</P>
<P>
He expressed his "deepest sorrow and condolences" to the
parents of the seven Israeli girls killed and another six wounded
by a Jordanian soldier this morning in the northern Baqura area
near the Jordanian-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process continues" despite the violence and the
current stagnation of Jordan's efforts to curb Israeli
government's Jewish settlement policy, said the King.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will rally up efforts to foster love, peace and
cooperation in the future to protect the generations to come,
said the King who was accompanied by Crown Prince Hassan and Prime
Minister Abdul Karim Kabariti.
</P>
<P>
Ahammad Musa, the murderer who is a driver in the Jordanian
army, has been arrested and under examination.
</P>
<P>
The Crown Prince this afternoon said that he felt "ashamed" for
the incident to happen in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Kabariti said in a press conference this afternoon that the
murderer would be treated with "the maximum punishment". 
</P>
</TEXT>
