<HEADLINE> 20 Foreigners Held Hostage in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The French Embassy to Nigeria
today confirmed that 20 foreign nationals, including 16 French,
three British and one American, have been held hostage off the
Nigerian coast by local people.
</P>
<P>
The foreigners were working on an oil platform belonging to
the ETPM company of France, which is currently trying to contact
them in Warri town, Delta state, southern Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The villagers who are holding the foreign nationals have not
made any demand so far, according to a French Foreign Ministry
statement this morning.
</P>
<P>
But the statement did not say when the incident happened.
</P>
<P>
The French Embassy said "the situation is quiet" in Warri and
negotiation is underway between ETPM and villagers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a source close to the foreign business circle in
Lagos told Xinhua that oil workers in Worri are said to be on
strike for better pay. However, this cannot be confirmed at the
moment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
