<HEADLINE> Consumer Education Urged in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The Consumer Council of Zimbabwe
(CCZ) today said there was great need to intensify consumer education
and awareness on sustainable consumption.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to be released ahead of the commemoration of
the World Consumer Rights Day to be held on March 15, the CCZ said
sustainable consumption should result in the ability to fulfill
basic human needs without destroying the environment.
</P>
<P>
It said the rate at which the world population was growing was a
serious cause for concern because the environment was at risk with
statistics showing that one percent of the world's tropical forest
was lost every year.
</P>
<P>
More than two million deaths a year could be traced to water
scarcity and pollution and heaps of waste were getting bigger
everyday, it said.
</P>
<P>
The CCZ said huge amounts of fish had been killed in Lake Chivero
due to the uncontrolled introduction of sewage into Harare's river
system that feeds into water reservoirs, resulting in the high court
orderering the City Council to stop further discharge of sludge into
rivers. enditem


