<HEADLINE> UN Assembly Urges Israel to Stop Illegal Housing Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, March 13 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. General Assembly
voted on Thursday to urge Israel to call of its plan to build
6,500 houses in the occupied East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution, which was approved by 130-3, the General
Assembly expressed deep concern at the decision of the government
of Israel to initiate new settlement activities in the Jebel Abu
Ghneim area in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that such settlements are "illegal and a major
obstacle to peace. Israel and the United States voted against the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which was sponsored by 42 countries, called
upon the Israeli authorities to refrain from all actions or
measures, including settlement activities, which alter the facts
on the ground, pre-empting the final status negotiations, and
have negative implication for the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
It called upon Israel, the occupying power, to abide
scrupulously by its legal obligations and responsibilities under
the Geneva Convention relative to the Protection of Civilian
Persons in Time of War of 12 August 1949, which is applicable to
all the territories occupied by Israel since 1967.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
