<HEADLINE> New Yorkers More Upbeat About their City: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, March 13 (Xinhua) -- New Yorkers are more upbeat
about their city than they have been in nearly a decade ago, with
their views of crime, the economy ad the future suggesting that
many have discarded the grim self-image that gripped them just
four years ago.
</P>
<P>
This scenario was given by the New York Times which conducted a
poll on March 1 through 6 in all parts of New York City. The poll
is based on telephone interviews with 1,397 adults. The margin of
the sampling error was plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
In one measure of how sharply attitudes have changed, half the
people surveyed said that even if they had the option to move
away, they would not leave New York. That was the highest
percentage that response to that question received in more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four percent of respondents said life in New York was
generally better, with 33 percent saying worse and 29 percent
saying the same. By contrast, four years ago, only 10 percent said
the state of the city was better than it had been. In this poll,
43 percent called the city safer than it was four years ago. In
1993, only 13 percent said they thought the city was safe. The
poll indicates that 59 percent described the city economy as good,
compared with 32 percent in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Still, New Yorkers have reservations about the city. They are
increasingly worried about the state of school, with one in five
voters saying that education should be the top priority of the
next government. One in four voters said that crime should be the
next Mayor's top priority.
</P>
<P>
The poll presented two areas that most accounted for New
Yorkers' improved feelings about the city are crime and the
economy. In terms of economy, 59 percent of New Yorkers now rate
it as good. And in another sign of a favorable mood about New
York, the percentage of New Yorkers who reported that they or a
member of their family had been a victim of a crime over the last
year fell from 27 percent in 1993 to 17 percent now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
